233
00:09:53,492 --> 00:09:56,095
HE KIND OF PRACTICED(?) ALONE

234
00:09:56,162 --> 00:09:58,364
-Talk to Da-hee for now.
-Okay.

235
00:10:00,333 --> 00:10:02,802
Please give me your business card
when you open a restaurant.

236
00:10:02,868 --> 00:10:04,437
-Yes, sure.
-Rok.

237
00:10:08,407 --> 00:10:11,210
-Why is your mouth squirming?
-Why did you move your mouth?

238
00:10:11,277 --> 00:10:12,278
What was that?

239
00:10:12,345 --> 00:10:13,879
What was that mouth?

240
00:10:13,946 --> 00:10:15,781
That's a new way of flirting.

241
00:10:15,848 --> 00:10:17,383
His mouth goes first.

242
00:10:18,150 --> 00:10:19,752
It's a new technique.

243
00:10:19,819 --> 00:10:20,920
-His mouth goes first.
-His mouth went first,

244
00:10:20,987 --> 00:10:22,755
-not his eyes.
-That was odd.

245
00:10:22,822 --> 00:10:28,494
Anyway, Da-hee had a special reason
for visiting <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> today.

246
00:10:28,561 --> 00:10:31,397
It feels a bit wrong
to promote my work out in the open.

247
00:10:31,464 --> 00:10:33,099
-It's all right.
-Are you sure?

248
00:10:33,165 --> 00:10:35,768
On top of that,
it's not the same network as this one.

249
00:10:35,835 --> 00:10:37,770
-It's not on JTBC?
-It's not?

250
00:10:37,837 --> 00:10:39,872
-You didn't know?
-I see.

251
00:10:39,939 --> 00:10:41,774
Really? Then don't do it.

252
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:43,776
-Let's hear her out.
-Shall we?

253
00:10:43,843 --> 00:10:46,145
-You can edit it out later.
-Right.

254
00:10:46,212 --> 00:10:48,147
-We'll hear you out.
-Okay.

255
00:10:48,214 --> 00:10:51,851
The first episode airs
at 8:50 p.m. on March 31st.

256
00:10:51,917 --> 00:10:53,953
It's a drama called <i>The Divorce Insurance,</i>

257
00:10:54,020 --> 00:10:57,657
<i>starring Lee Dong-wook, Lee Kwang-soo,</i>
<i>and Lee Joo-been.</i>

258
00:10:57,723 --> 00:11:00,192
-Please tune in.
-All right.

259
00:11:00,259 --> 00:11:02,762
I don't think it'll go on air.

260
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:06,766
-All right.
-It airs on Mondays and Tuesdays, right?

261
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:12,004
And now, we're going to turn
Da-hee's fridge inside out.

262
00:11:12,071 --> 00:11:15,541
I see that she has two fridges here.

263
00:11:15,608 --> 00:11:17,109
Do you use both alone?

264
00:11:17,176 --> 00:11:20,880
No, I live with my parents,
so we use those together.

265
00:11:20,946 --> 00:11:22,314
-I see.
-She must have lots of food.

266
00:11:22,381 --> 00:11:25,051
You give off that city girl vibe.

267
00:11:25,117 --> 00:11:26,686
What do you think she'll have?

268
00:11:26,752 --> 00:11:29,889
-Definitely all three great delicacies.
-The three great delicacies.

269
00:11:29,955 --> 00:11:30,956
And beef.

270
00:11:31,023 --> 00:11:33,526
-She'll probably have more beef than pork.
-Right, beef.

271
00:11:33,592 --> 00:11:36,762
Did your mother say anything like,
"Don't overuse the ingredients"?

272
00:11:36,829 --> 00:11:40,332
She was worried the food would spoil
in the process of moving everything.

273
00:11:40,399 --> 00:11:43,002
-But you had a system for doing this.
-Yes, we do.

274
00:11:43,069 --> 00:11:44,704
Do you see these gloves?

275
00:11:44,770 --> 00:11:47,173
Hygiene is something we prioritize here.

276
00:11:47,239 --> 00:11:49,375
-Shall we take a look?
-Yes, we shall.

277
00:11:49,442 --> 00:11:51,377
This is the first time

278
00:11:51,444 --> 00:11:54,180
we had two fridges
after the new season began.

279
00:11:54,246 --> 00:11:58,017
Let's find out what ingredients
Da-hee has in her fridges.

280
00:11:58,084 --> 00:12:00,786
We present Da-hee's fridge!

281
00:12:00,853 --> 00:12:01,887
HEART RACING

282
00:12:01,954 --> 00:12:04,223
-That's crazy.
-My gosh.

283
00:12:05,524 --> 00:12:07,893
-That's crazy.
-My gosh.

284
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:09,361
Are those meat?

285
00:12:09,428 --> 00:12:11,030
THE FRIDGE ALREADY LOOKS FULL

286
00:12:11,530 --> 00:12:12,965
She must like meat.

287
00:12:13,032 --> 00:12:15,234
-Look at how neatly organized they are.
-She has different types too.

288
00:12:15,301 --> 00:12:17,236
Everything is neatly organized.

289
00:12:17,303 --> 00:12:19,839
DA-HEE'S FRIDGE LOOKS PERFECT
IN EVERY SHELF

290
00:12:19,905 --> 00:12:22,308
-It's as if we're at a butcher shop.
-Right?

291
00:12:22,374 --> 00:12:24,977
The top shelf of the fridge.

292
00:12:25,044 --> 00:12:27,179
There are different kinds of <i>ssamjang.</i>

293
00:12:27,246 --> 00:12:30,316
-Many fermented sauces.
-Yes, that's gochujang.

294
00:12:30,382 --> 00:12:32,017
-Seasoned <i>ssamjang.</i>
-<i>Ssamjang.</i>

295
00:12:32,084 --> 00:12:34,954
And these are side dishes.

296
00:12:35,020 --> 00:12:36,522
I want to try a few already.

297
00:12:36,589 --> 00:12:38,591
I often eat at home,

298
00:12:38,657 --> 00:12:41,961
so she always makes side dishes,
especially seasoned greens.

299
00:12:42,027 --> 00:12:43,395
What's your favorite?

300
00:12:43,462 --> 00:12:45,498
I really love seasoned seaweed stems.

301
00:12:45,564 --> 00:12:48,367
-My mom made that.
-This one.

302
00:12:48,434 --> 00:12:52,138
She crushes garlic into large pieces,
then stir-fries everything in perilla oil.

303
00:12:52,204 --> 00:12:54,240
-Perilla oil?
-Yes, she loves to use that.

304
00:12:54,306 --> 00:12:56,408
-That's perilla oil.
-This one?

305
00:12:56,475 --> 00:12:58,677
-She pressed it herself.
-This one?

306
00:12:58,744 --> 00:13:01,547
-She pressed this at a mill?
-Yes.

307
00:13:01,614 --> 00:13:04,817
-We use it for all seasoned green dishes.
-For everything?

308
00:13:04,884 --> 00:13:07,520
-Perilla oil?
-She likes perilla oil.

309
00:13:07,586 --> 00:13:09,522
-This is <i>mukeunji.</i>
-Yes, that's right.

310
00:13:09,588 --> 00:13:11,624
Do you eat this with meat?

311
00:13:11,690 --> 00:13:15,561
I eat that when I'm on a diet.

312
00:13:15,628 --> 00:13:19,131
I wash it with water
and mix it with brown rice and tuna.

313
00:13:19,198 --> 00:13:21,233
-I see.
-That was my staple.

314
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:23,068
And I'm seeing some vegetables.

315
00:13:23,135 --> 00:13:24,837
-This is full too.
-That's a lot.

316
00:13:24,904 --> 00:13:27,940
She has cabbage, onions,

317
00:13:28,007 --> 00:13:30,643
bean sprout, and zucchini.

318
00:13:30,709 --> 00:13:32,178
-Dried persimmon.
-This one.

319
00:13:32,244 --> 00:13:33,612
And in here. What are these?

320
00:13:33,679 --> 00:13:34,780
-Radish.
-Radish!

321
00:13:34,847 --> 00:13:36,448
-Do you like radish?
-Why do you have so many?

322
00:13:36,515 --> 00:13:39,652
My dad farms as a hobby

323
00:13:39,718 --> 00:13:41,620
and brings home lots of vegetables.

324
00:13:41,687 --> 00:13:43,889
My mom freezes everything he brings.

325
00:13:43,956 --> 00:13:46,425
-Right here. Chives and…
-Yes.

326
00:13:46,492 --> 00:13:48,661
-You're right.
-Red chili pepper, green chili pepper.

327
00:13:48,727 --> 00:13:50,062
-Shiitake.
-Garlic.

328
00:13:50,129 --> 00:13:52,298
-Yes, date and shiitake too.
-Date.

329
00:13:52,364 --> 00:13:54,533
-He grows shiitake too?
-Yes, he does.

330
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:57,136
-Right here.
-He grew those?

331
00:13:57,203 --> 00:13:59,338
HE TAKES HIS HOBBY SERIOUSLY
HE EVEN GROWS HIS OWN SHIITAKE

332
00:13:59,405 --> 00:14:01,273
-You need a log to grow that.
-Right.

333
00:14:01,340 --> 00:14:03,342
He'd make holes with a drill,

334
00:14:03,409 --> 00:14:06,512
then my mom and I put in
the fungus in the holes.

335
00:14:06,579 --> 00:14:08,280
-We did that together.
-My gosh.

336
00:14:08,347 --> 00:14:10,149
You were the first
to grow your own mushroom.

337
00:14:10,216 --> 00:14:12,484
You'll end up raising cows too.

338
00:14:12,551 --> 00:14:13,953
I mean, you like meat.

339
00:14:14,019 --> 00:14:17,223
Wait a second. There's refined rice wine.

340
00:14:17,289 --> 00:14:19,992
Hey, let's talk about this.

341
00:14:20,059 --> 00:14:21,560
It's pretty huge.

342
00:14:21,627 --> 00:14:25,497
Wait, that's something
my dad drinks with his meals.

343
00:14:25,564 --> 00:14:27,433
-He drinks this?
-Yes, he does.

344
00:14:27,499 --> 00:14:29,235
-I'm more into soju.
-Soju.

345
00:14:29,301 --> 00:14:30,836
So I don't really like refined rice wine.

346
00:14:30,903 --> 00:14:32,805
Do you drink soju often?

347
00:14:32,872 --> 00:14:35,274
Yes, I can hold my alcohol.

348
00:14:35,341 --> 00:14:38,644
-She can beat most men.
-Really?

349
00:14:38,711 --> 00:14:41,280
"I can hold my alcohol"
had an underlying meaning.

350
00:14:41,347 --> 00:14:44,884
She can hold it for sure. She's the same
throughout the night, until the end.

351
00:14:44,950 --> 00:14:46,352
SHE'S FINE

352
00:14:46,418 --> 00:14:48,921
Then what's DEX like after a drink?

353
00:14:48,988 --> 00:14:52,658
-I'm the opposite. I get hammered.
-Do you get drunk?

354
00:14:52,725 --> 00:14:56,629
I think he becomes
a bit cuter than he is now.

355
00:14:56,695 --> 00:14:57,930
The freezer.

356
00:14:57,997 --> 00:15:00,466
These are noodles.

357
00:15:00,532 --> 00:15:02,501
<i>-Naengmyeon.</i>
<i>-Naengmyeon.</i>

358
00:15:02,568 --> 00:15:04,069
Do you enjoy noodles?

359
00:15:04,136 --> 00:15:07,640
I eat the dish for the sour taste.
I don't get what the noodles are about.

360
00:15:07,706 --> 00:15:09,308
It's just for the vinegar.

361
00:15:09,375 --> 00:15:11,477
You'd see a bottle at a restaurant, right?

362
00:15:11,543 --> 00:15:14,513
-I add in more than half the bottle.
-Of the vinegar?

363
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:15,581
-Yes.
-I like the sour taste too.

364
00:15:15,648 --> 00:15:17,383
-So you like the sour taste.
-I do.

365
00:15:17,449 --> 00:15:20,419
If they're going to make something,
would you like it to be sour?

366
00:15:20,486 --> 00:15:23,622
I always like cold broth
with a touch of vinegar,

367
00:15:23,689 --> 00:15:27,860
but I find it weird
when something hot tastes sour.

368
00:15:27,927 --> 00:15:29,361
How about sour <i>doenjang jjigae</i>?

369
00:15:29,428 --> 00:15:31,730
-That means it's spoiled.
-Yes, it is.

370
00:15:32,731 --> 00:15:35,968
If a hot dish tastes sour,
it means it's spoiled.

371
00:15:36,035 --> 00:15:40,906
-And Da-hee's favorite, meat.
-There are lots.

372
00:15:40,973 --> 00:15:44,610
Gosh, are these different cuts?

373
00:15:44,677 --> 00:15:47,980
Shin fore shank, beef brisket.
It's all written on the bag.

374
00:15:48,047 --> 00:15:49,815
This is for soup, this is for grilling.

375
00:15:49,882 --> 00:15:52,117
-That's right.
-Everything is separated.

376
00:15:52,184 --> 00:15:58,624
I get a kick out of cutting up meat
and separating them into portions.

377
00:15:58,691 --> 00:16:01,427
I don't know why, but I like to prep meat.

378
00:16:01,493 --> 00:16:04,229
-But the butcher shop does it for you.
-Well, you know.

379
00:16:04,296 --> 00:16:06,432
They sell whole cuts at Costco,

380
00:16:06,498 --> 00:16:09,368
and I like to cut it up
and prep everything myself.

381
00:16:09,435 --> 00:16:10,502
You can run a butcher shop yourself.

382
00:16:10,569 --> 00:16:12,905
GRAND OPENING:
DA-HEE'S BUTCHER SHOP

383
00:16:12,972 --> 00:16:14,306
-Look at this.
-What's that?

384
00:16:14,373 --> 00:16:16,742
-These are seafood.
-Seafood.

385
00:16:16,809 --> 00:16:20,212
We're by the sea now.
I'm seeing lots of fish.

386
00:16:20,279 --> 00:16:21,513
What's your favorite fish?

387
00:16:21,580 --> 00:16:23,582
I don't really like fish.

388
00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:25,150
-Do you not like seafood?
-No.

389
00:16:25,217 --> 00:16:27,353
My parents love them.

390
00:16:27,419 --> 00:16:28,754
I see.

391
00:16:28,821 --> 00:16:30,255
-<i>Gukjang?</i>
-<i>Gukjang</i>?

392
00:16:30,322 --> 00:16:31,790
<i>-Gukjang.</i>
<i>-Cheonggukjang.</i>

393
00:16:31,857 --> 00:16:33,392
-Do you like it?
-I do.

394
00:16:33,459 --> 00:16:36,228
-You do?
-I do. I like all fermented pastes.

395
00:16:36,295 --> 00:16:38,097
Then you must like Korean cuisine.

396
00:16:38,163 --> 00:16:40,666
I'm a total Korean cuisine person.

397
00:16:41,767 --> 00:16:42,768
You're right.

398
00:16:42,835 --> 00:16:45,971
This wasn't the fridge
that DEX imagined to see.

399
00:16:46,038 --> 00:16:49,008
Yes, I'm seeing lots of Korean touches.

400
00:16:49,074 --> 00:16:50,075
-Right?
-Yes.

401
00:16:50,142 --> 00:16:53,078
-She doesn't even have cheese.
-She doesn't.

402
00:16:53,145 --> 00:16:54,513
But there's another one.

403
00:16:54,580 --> 00:16:57,716
I may see the things I expected
in that one.

404
00:16:57,783 --> 00:17:00,586
-Yes, the three great delicacies.
-The three great delicacies.

405
00:17:00,652 --> 00:17:02,221
Let's open it up.

406
00:17:03,122 --> 00:17:05,557
WHAT'S IN THE OTHER FRIDGE?

407
00:17:06,158 --> 00:17:07,526
Let's open it up.

408
00:17:09,962 --> 00:17:11,964
-It's a kimchi fridge.
-It's a kimchi fridge.

409
00:17:12,031 --> 00:17:14,800
-It's a kimchi fridge.
-Yes, we have a separate one at home.

410
00:17:14,867 --> 00:17:17,036
-You have many different kinds of kimchi.
-Yes.

411
00:17:17,102 --> 00:17:18,570
She must make kimchi every year.

412
00:17:18,637 --> 00:17:20,806
-You're right.
-This one was made in 2024.

413
00:17:20,873 --> 00:17:24,176
-This is from 2023.
-What? 2023?

414
00:17:24,243 --> 00:17:25,844
-That's vintage.
-This is from 2023.

415
00:17:25,911 --> 00:17:29,481
We bury older kimchi in Anseong.

416
00:17:29,548 --> 00:17:32,551
<i>-We bury it in the ground.</i>
<i>-In a crock?</i>

417
00:17:32,618 --> 00:17:33,652
She even has crocks.

418
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:36,789
And we bring however much we want to eat
whenever we go over there.

419
00:17:36,855 --> 00:17:38,891
Cooking with matured kimchi
makes food taste great.

420
00:17:38,957 --> 00:17:40,392
Well-ripened radish kimchi.

421
00:17:40,459 --> 00:17:42,194
-And white kimchi too.
-That's right.

422
00:17:44,263 --> 00:17:47,099
-This family is serious about kimchi.
-Tell me about it.

423
00:17:47,166 --> 00:17:50,402
"Da-hee's young radish kimchi,
Dad's young radish kimchi."

424
00:17:50,469 --> 00:17:51,537
What's the difference?

425
00:17:51,603 --> 00:17:54,606
My dad doesn't like sour taste.

426
00:17:54,673 --> 00:17:56,975
I like everything sour,
so it's fermented longer

427
00:17:57,042 --> 00:17:58,510
-and made sour.
-She likes well-ripened kimchi.

428
00:17:58,577 --> 00:17:59,845
-You like that sour taste.
-Yes.

429
00:17:59,912 --> 00:18:02,481
-Do you not like <i>geotjeori</i>?
-I don't.

430
00:18:02,548 --> 00:18:05,551
This family is serious
about Korean cuisine.

431
00:18:05,617 --> 00:18:08,554
That was all for Da-hee's fridge.

432
00:18:08,620 --> 00:18:10,422
WILL THE CHEFS
CAPTURE HER PALATE?

433
00:18:10,489 --> 00:18:13,592
Let's find out the fridge owner's orders

434
00:18:13,659 --> 00:18:17,763
and decide on the contenders
for each order.

435
00:18:17,830 --> 00:18:19,998
Please show us the orders.

436
00:18:20,065 --> 00:18:21,433
LEE DA-HEE'S FRIDGE COMPETITION

437
00:18:21,500 --> 00:18:23,735
"Kimchi dish to Paradise."

438
00:18:24,470 --> 00:18:26,271
-That's smart.
-That's a term from <i>Single's Inferno</i>.

439
00:18:26,338 --> 00:18:28,507
Yes, between Inferno and Paradise.

440
00:18:28,574 --> 00:18:30,876
I have a lot of kimchi to work with,

441
00:18:30,943 --> 00:18:33,312
but there's a limit
to the kind of dishes I can make,

442
00:18:33,378 --> 00:18:37,716
such as kimchi <i>jjigae</i>
or stir-fried pork with kimchi.

443
00:18:37,783 --> 00:18:41,520
I thought the chefs could make
something different with kimchi,

444
00:18:41,587 --> 00:18:44,823
-and I wanted to learn from them.
-Right, of course.

445
00:18:44,890 --> 00:18:46,658
-A new kind of kimchi dish.
-Yes.

446
00:18:46,725 --> 00:18:48,560
What's the second order?

447
00:18:48,627 --> 00:18:52,164
<i>-First encounters are always so hard</i>
<i>-Always so hard</i>

448
00:18:52,798 --> 00:18:53,799
Is that the song?

449
00:18:53,866 --> 00:18:55,100
Yes, it is.

450
00:18:55,167 --> 00:18:57,503
Why did you use those lyrics?

451
00:18:57,569 --> 00:18:58,704
-But wait.
-Yes?

452
00:18:58,770 --> 00:19:00,205
-You know this song?
-Come on.

453
00:19:00,272 --> 00:19:03,709
COME ON! DON'T BE LIKE THAT!

454
00:19:03,775 --> 00:19:05,878
-Do you want to see the dance too?
-Do you know it?

455
00:19:05,944 --> 00:19:07,312
-Jeez.
-Jeez.

456
00:19:07,379 --> 00:19:08,680
We're running out of time.

457
00:19:10,282 --> 00:19:12,451
Do you need to have
a first taste in something?

458
00:19:12,518 --> 00:19:15,988
I always end up eating the same thing
when I'm working.

459
00:19:16,054 --> 00:19:17,689
I'd eat flour food, <i>ramyeon</i>, Korean food,

460
00:19:17,756 --> 00:19:19,925
<i>jjajangmyeon</i>, or <i>jjamppong</i>.

461
00:19:19,992 --> 00:19:24,196
I'm not opposed to trying new food,
but I can never think of anything.

462
00:19:24,263 --> 00:19:26,765
-The first flavor.
-Yes, the first flavor.

463
00:19:26,832 --> 00:19:29,468
-The first flavor.
-You're right. It's the first flavor.

464
00:19:29,535 --> 00:19:30,969
This will require creativity.

465
00:19:31,036 --> 00:19:33,739
She wants to try something new

466
00:19:33,805 --> 00:19:36,008
as opposed to something
that already exists.

467
00:19:36,074 --> 00:19:38,777
Kang-rok, do you want the first call?

468
00:19:38,844 --> 00:19:39,845
Yes.

469
00:19:40,345 --> 00:19:42,014
-Do you want it?
-I'll take

470
00:19:42,080 --> 00:19:44,049
the second order.

471
00:19:44,116 --> 00:19:45,584
The second order. What is it?

472
00:19:45,651 --> 00:19:47,786
-First flavors are always so hard.
-How is it done?

473
00:19:50,189 --> 00:19:51,190
First…

474
00:19:53,559 --> 00:19:56,461
What do you want to do now?
You have to do it for us.

475
00:19:56,528 --> 00:19:58,030
Flavors…

476
00:19:58,096 --> 00:19:59,932
A GREAT IMPROVEMENT,
SINGING JUST THREE SYLLABLES

477
00:19:59,998 --> 00:20:03,669
-I'll do first flavors are always so hard.
-First flavors are always so hard.

478
00:20:03,735 --> 00:20:06,271
-Then, I'll go.
-Chef Hyun-suk.

479
00:20:06,338 --> 00:20:08,507
-First flavors are always so hard.
-What?

480
00:20:08,574 --> 00:20:10,642
I'll let you taste something

481
00:20:10,709 --> 00:20:12,644
-you have never had before.
-It's a big match.

482
00:20:12,711 --> 00:20:14,213
I see.

483
00:20:14,279 --> 00:20:15,781
Yes, all right.

484
00:20:15,847 --> 00:20:18,784
Kang-rok just bit his lips.

485
00:20:18,850 --> 00:20:23,021
-I can't take it back, can I?
-No, you can't.

486
00:20:23,088 --> 00:20:25,190
The strongest contender is up.

487
00:20:25,257 --> 00:20:27,659
We need two chefs to work with kimchi.

488
00:20:27,726 --> 00:20:29,561
-A new dish with kimchi.
-Hey.

489
00:20:29,628 --> 00:20:31,263
-Oh my.
-Chef Jong-won.

490
00:20:31,330 --> 00:20:33,198
But kimchi isn't Western cuisine.

491
00:20:33,265 --> 00:20:35,767
I'm going to make Korean cuisine today.

492
00:20:36,335 --> 00:20:37,703
CHEF GOOD VIBES IS GOOD
AT MAKING KOREAN CUISINE TOO?

493
00:20:37,769 --> 00:20:40,038
-I currently run two restaurants.
-That's right.

494
00:20:40,105 --> 00:20:42,908
One of them is Western cuisine
and the other is Korean cuisine.

495
00:20:42,975 --> 00:20:43,976
He makes Korean food too.

496
00:20:44,042 --> 00:20:47,179
-Who'll go up against him?
-And now, everyone eyes each other.

497
00:20:47,246 --> 00:20:48,547
-Nam-no.
-I'll go for kimchi.

498
00:20:48,614 --> 00:20:52,384
-The anti-Chef Good Vibes.
-Chef Anti-Good Vibes.

499
00:20:52,451 --> 00:20:54,953
Good cooks
aren't supposed to be good-looking.

500
00:20:55,020 --> 00:20:56,521
THIS ROCK-SOLID PHILOSOPHY
BROUGHT THEM TOGETHER

501
00:20:56,588 --> 00:20:57,689
It's a plus if you're handsome.

502
00:20:57,756 --> 00:21:02,027
-Chef Anti-Good Vibes.
-Chef Anti-Good Vibes?

503
00:21:02,594 --> 00:21:04,930
BUT THE CHAIR OF THE ANTI-GOOD VIBES
LOST TO CHEF GOOD VIBES

504
00:21:04,997 --> 00:21:07,966
I'll start a revolution
and fight against him.

505
00:21:08,033 --> 00:21:09,835
-Someone has to teach him a lesson.
-Yes.

506
00:21:09,901 --> 00:21:12,104
CHEF ANTI-GOOD VIBES
CHALLENGE CHEF GOOD VIBES

507
00:21:12,170 --> 00:21:15,173
Nam-no wants to see Jong-won go down.

508
00:21:15,240 --> 00:21:16,708
-I'll get your revenge.
-Okay.

509
00:21:16,775 --> 00:21:19,011
Nam-no chooses this one. That's great.

510
00:21:19,077 --> 00:21:23,115
This is the first round
with Da-hee's ingredients.

511
00:21:23,181 --> 00:21:26,351
Chef Good Vibes,
the kind-hearted Son Jong-won versus…

512
00:21:26,418 --> 00:21:27,419
Wait.

513
00:21:27,486 --> 00:21:30,022
…Chef Anti-Good Vibes,

514
00:21:30,088 --> 00:21:33,358
-the faint-hearted Yoon Nam-no.
-I see.

515
00:21:33,425 --> 00:21:35,727
It's a battle between Chef Good Vibes
and Chef Anti-Good Vibes.

516
00:21:35,794 --> 00:21:37,529
The two are in a competition.

517
00:21:37,596 --> 00:21:39,865
Only one of the two
is in this competition.

518
00:21:40,732 --> 00:21:44,703
Yoon Nam-no, the action-taker
of the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance.

519
00:21:44,770 --> 00:21:48,206
But you have this cuteness
that Chef Jong-won can't compare to.

520
00:21:48,273 --> 00:21:50,676
-Of course.
-The Fu Bao of chefs.

521
00:21:50,742 --> 00:21:52,377
-He's cute.
-Fu Bao is adorable.

522
00:21:52,444 --> 00:21:54,546
-According to the production crew…
-Yes?

523
00:21:54,613 --> 00:21:57,883
…he's now against Chef Jong-won
as the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance,

524
00:21:57,949 --> 00:22:01,219
but Jong-won is actually his role model.

525
00:22:01,286 --> 00:22:03,322
-You're right.
-You have a lot of respect for him.

526
00:22:03,388 --> 00:22:06,224
I believe there are
two phenomenal Sons in Korea.

527
00:22:06,291 --> 00:22:07,926
-Two phenomenal Sons.
-One of them is Son Heung-min.

528
00:22:07,993 --> 00:22:10,495
And among chefs, we have Son Jong-won.

529
00:22:10,562 --> 00:22:13,231
-That's the best compliment.
-He's that great, huh?

530
00:22:13,298 --> 00:22:17,202
He's the top chef people in my generation
wants to work for

531
00:22:17,269 --> 00:22:19,638
and learn from.

532
00:22:19,705 --> 00:22:21,707
-I'm actually thrilled right now.
-Really?

533
00:22:21,773 --> 00:22:22,974
How do you feel right now?

534
00:22:23,041 --> 00:22:27,112
He just confessed
his true feelings about you.

535
00:22:27,179 --> 00:22:29,915
Why is he saying that?
To set this up for what?

536
00:22:29,981 --> 00:22:32,484
I'm a bit worried right now.

537
00:22:32,551 --> 00:22:34,219
You're wary of him.

538
00:22:34,286 --> 00:22:37,389
When the chefs made their choices,

539
00:22:37,456 --> 00:22:40,859
I didn't think
Chef Jong-won would choose my order.

540
00:22:40,926 --> 00:22:42,728
I've only seen him make Western cuisine.

541
00:22:42,794 --> 00:22:45,464
-Right?
-It was a surprise, and I loved it.

542
00:22:45,530 --> 00:22:49,468
-I'm looking forward to his dish.
-I see.

543
00:22:49,534 --> 00:22:50,869
Can you make a good kimchi dish too?

544
00:22:50,936 --> 00:22:53,772
I actually make kimchi quite often.

545
00:22:53,839 --> 00:22:56,408
I personally make
the kimchi I serve at my restaurant.

546
00:22:56,475 --> 00:22:59,244
You said you've made kimchi with
over 5,000 cabbage heads. Is that right?

547
00:22:59,311 --> 00:23:02,614
That sounds about right.

548
00:23:02,681 --> 00:23:06,284
Chef Nam-no has also worked with
5,000 cabbage heads.

549
00:23:07,052 --> 00:23:08,053
WHOA

550
00:23:08,120 --> 00:23:09,888
-He's eaten that much.
-I see.

551
00:23:09,955 --> 00:23:12,891
-You can't beat a guy who eats a lot.
-He loves kimchi.

552
00:23:12,958 --> 00:23:16,561
The chef who has eaten more
may have an advantage in this.

553
00:23:17,496 --> 00:23:19,664
CHEF JONG-WON: BLANCHED PEPPER LEAVES,
TUNA SAUCE, RED PEPPER POWDER, BONE BROTH,

554
00:23:19,731 --> 00:23:21,900
RADISH KIMCHI, DRIED PERSIMMON,
APPLE VINEGAR, NAENGMYEON, AND MORE

555
00:23:21,967 --> 00:23:24,636
I'm going to make a dish called

556
00:23:24,703 --> 00:23:27,672
Kimchi Fine Da-heening.

557
00:23:28,874 --> 00:23:32,210
-Kimchi Fine Da-heening.
-Da-heening.

558
00:23:32,277 --> 00:23:35,247
-Not dining, but Da-heening.
-It's Da-heening?

559
00:23:35,313 --> 00:23:37,082
He added a personalized touch.

560
00:23:37,149 --> 00:23:40,485
I prepared a dish called <i>bojagi </i>kimchi,
which originates from Kaesong.

561
00:23:40,552 --> 00:23:45,023
It's a fermented dish made with
seafood wrapped up in kimchi.

562
00:23:45,090 --> 00:23:47,526
But instead of seafood, she had <i>jokbal</i>,

563
00:23:47,592 --> 00:23:49,761
so I want to use that
and add some noodles too.

564
00:23:49,828 --> 00:23:51,797
It'll make a nice meal on its own.

565
00:23:51,863 --> 00:23:53,265
You're adding noodles to kimchi?

566
00:23:53,331 --> 00:23:57,269
<i>It's a mix of Pyongyang-style naengmyeon</i>
<i>and bojagi </i>kimchi.

567
00:23:57,335 --> 00:23:58,503
HIGH EXPECTATION

568
00:23:58,570 --> 00:23:59,971
<i>Bojagi</i> kimchi.

569
00:24:00,038 --> 00:24:02,507
CHEF YOON NAM-NO: WASHED MUKEUNJI,
BLACK GARLIC SALT, BLANCHED PEPPER LEAVES,

570
00:24:02,574 --> 00:24:04,743
SMOKY FLAVORED OIL, PICKLED CHILI PEPPER,
OLIVE OIL, NABAK-KIMCHI, ENOKI, AND MORE

571
00:24:04,810 --> 00:24:07,412
Chef Nam-no, what's your dish?

572
00:24:07,479 --> 00:24:09,080
My dish is called

573
00:24:09,147 --> 00:24:11,116
Kimchi Street Fight.

574
00:24:12,651 --> 00:24:15,854
-Kimchi Street Fight.
-Street Fight.

575
00:24:15,921 --> 00:24:18,890
He's going to start this fight and win.

576
00:24:18,957 --> 00:24:19,991
Please explain your dish.

577
00:24:20,058 --> 00:24:23,895
I'll make a dressing with <i>nabak</i>-kimchi,

578
00:24:23,962 --> 00:24:27,365
<i>-ratatouille with </i>mukeunji<i>…</i>
<i>-Ratatouille?</i>

579
00:24:27,432 --> 00:24:29,100
<i>…and serve it with lamb chops.</i>

580
00:24:29,167 --> 00:24:32,637
Kimchi won't work as the main character,
but it'll play a solid supporting part.

581
00:24:32,704 --> 00:24:35,807
I'll turn it into a scene stealer.

582
00:24:35,874 --> 00:24:37,742
It's so interesting

583
00:24:37,809 --> 00:24:42,714
that I can already see their personality
through the names of the dishes.

584
00:24:42,781 --> 00:24:45,317
-Was it especially so for Street Fight?
-No.

585
00:24:45,383 --> 00:24:49,588
I think that spirit goes well
with who Chef Nam-no is.

586
00:24:49,654 --> 00:24:52,591
He has that masculinity and roughness.

587
00:24:52,657 --> 00:24:54,092
He's very competitive.

588
00:24:54,159 --> 00:24:57,829
Chef Nam-no is competitive
out in the open,

589
00:24:57,896 --> 00:25:00,799
but Chef Jong-won
is also burning with the desire to win.

590
00:25:00,866 --> 00:25:03,635
-He has that something in him.
-He sure does.

591
00:25:03,702 --> 00:25:06,771
We're about to begin
the 15-minute cook-off.

592
00:25:07,339 --> 00:25:08,373
WHOA

593
00:25:08,440 --> 00:25:12,777
He's going to start this street fight
against his role model, Son Jong-won.

594
00:25:12,844 --> 00:25:14,880
Chef Yoon Nam-no, the bulldozer.

595
00:25:14,946 --> 00:25:16,948
He's going to put kimchi
into his dish today

596
00:25:17,015 --> 00:25:20,285
and put Yoon Nam-no down for good too.

597
00:25:20,352 --> 00:25:24,523
-The phenomenal Son, Chef Son Jong-won.
-It's crazy.

598
00:25:24,589 --> 00:25:28,960
Which one of the chefs will take
their ticket to Paradise with kimchi?

599
00:25:29,027 --> 00:25:32,063
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

600
00:25:34,232 --> 00:25:35,634
Begin!

601
00:25:35,700 --> 00:25:37,235
HIS SIGNATURE SALUTE

602
00:25:38,336 --> 00:25:40,505
-It has begun.
-The order is kimchi.

603
00:25:40,572 --> 00:25:42,040
A new kind of kimchi dish.

604
00:25:42,107 --> 00:25:45,610
-They're both using zucchini.
-Zucchinis.

605
00:25:45,677 --> 00:25:47,279
-Zucchinis.
-They begin with zucchini.

606
00:25:47,345 --> 00:25:49,915
What are the chances?
They're both using zucchinis.

607
00:25:49,981 --> 00:25:51,449
They're cutting it similarly too.

608
00:25:51,516 --> 00:25:52,951
No, they're different.

609
00:25:53,018 --> 00:25:57,122
-Chef Nam-no cut out the seeds.
-Right.

610
00:25:57,188 --> 00:25:59,491
He's going to dice it up.

611
00:26:00,659 --> 00:26:02,027
He's parboiling the zucchini.

612
00:26:02,093 --> 00:26:06,965
It can get mushy, so he took it out
and cooled it in iced water.

613
00:26:07,832 --> 00:26:09,601
An apple.

614
00:26:09,668 --> 00:26:11,703
Chef Jong-won, what is that?

615
00:26:11,770 --> 00:26:13,805
-I'm cutting up <i>jokbal.</i>
-She had <i>jokbal</i>?

616
00:26:13,872 --> 00:26:15,440
-You had <i>jokbal.</i>
-I did.

617
00:26:15,507 --> 00:26:17,275
Chef Jong-won is using <i>jokbal</i>.

618
00:26:17,342 --> 00:26:20,946
That <i>jokbal </i>was already cooked,
so wouldn't it lose the flavor in water?

619
00:26:21,012 --> 00:26:24,649
-He's trying to make it bland.
-He doesn't want the seasoning.

620
00:26:24,716 --> 00:26:25,884
Do you like <i>jokbal</i>?

621
00:26:25,951 --> 00:26:28,019
I do. I bought that pack.

622
00:26:28,086 --> 00:26:29,421
-Did you?
-Yes.

623
00:26:29,487 --> 00:26:31,957
Nice choice. Good choice.

624
00:26:32,657 --> 00:26:35,026
-Nam-no is using mushroom.
-Enoki.

625
00:26:35,093 --> 00:26:38,296
-He's going to make ratatouille.
-Oh, that's for the ratatouille.

626
00:26:38,797 --> 00:26:43,368
2. OIL PAN AND STIR-FRY VEGETABLES
AND SALTED SHRIMP

627
00:26:44,269 --> 00:26:46,271
-Something already smells delicious.
-Does it?

628
00:26:46,338 --> 00:26:47,772
A ROUND COOKIE CUTTER

629
00:26:48,607 --> 00:26:51,242
MR. GOOD VIBES USES IT ON THE APPLE
TO MAKE A SHAPE

630
00:26:52,043 --> 00:26:55,280
HE PLACES ANOTHER CUTTER
ON THE INSIDE

631
00:26:55,780 --> 00:26:57,515
HE WANTS TO PULL IT OUT, BUT…

632
00:26:57,582 --> 00:27:00,452
-<i>Mukeunji.</i> Da-hee likes that too.
-The apple.

633
00:27:00,518 --> 00:27:01,686
He can't pull it out.

634
00:27:01,753 --> 00:27:04,489
He can't! He can't pull it out!

635
00:27:04,556 --> 00:27:06,291
He can't pull it out!

636
00:27:06,358 --> 00:27:07,592
-He can't pull it out!
-No!

637
00:27:07,659 --> 00:27:11,463
-He can't pull it out!
-Oh, no.

638
00:27:11,529 --> 00:27:12,964
HE CUTS THE EDGE

639
00:27:13,031 --> 00:27:14,833
The cookie cutter went in and…

640
00:27:14,899 --> 00:27:17,102
The apple ate it up.

641
00:27:17,168 --> 00:27:19,771
Are you using just the inside?
I hope you can pull it out.

642
00:27:21,106 --> 00:27:22,841
THE 1ST ATTEMPT
TO PULL OUT THE OUTER RING

643
00:27:22,907 --> 00:27:25,043
-He can't do it.
-It won't pop out.

644
00:27:25,110 --> 00:27:26,778
-He can't do it!
-Why isn't it popping out?

645
00:27:26,845 --> 00:27:28,980
He lost a lot of time.

646
00:27:29,547 --> 00:27:31,449
IT TOOK HIM 50 SECOND
TO PULL ONE OUT

647
00:27:31,516 --> 00:27:33,018
He's behind already.

648
00:27:33,084 --> 00:27:34,552
-What's he going to do?
-This was unexpected.

649
00:27:34,619 --> 00:27:36,388
Oh, no.

650
00:27:36,454 --> 00:27:39,591
-What is he going to do now?
-It's taking him 30 seconds.

651
00:27:39,658 --> 00:27:41,960
-Will he have to cut it?
-It's not coming out.

652
00:27:42,027 --> 00:27:43,895
What is he going to use that apple for?

653
00:27:43,962 --> 00:27:46,431
I guess he needs that shape.

654
00:27:46,498 --> 00:27:48,133
-Jong-won is in a crisis.
-Look at that.

655
00:27:48,199 --> 00:27:50,568
JONG-WON FALLS INTO A CRISIS

656
00:27:50,635 --> 00:27:53,004
THEY'RE ALSO GETTING NERVOUS

657
00:27:53,071 --> 00:27:54,339
He's in a crisis!

658
00:27:54,406 --> 00:27:56,975
HE FINALLY SUCCEEDS

659
00:27:57,042 --> 00:27:59,577
-He's working on the lamb chops now.
-He did it.

660
00:27:59,644 --> 00:28:02,781
-He just lost a minute and 30 seconds.
-Yes.

661
00:28:04,082 --> 00:28:07,118
JONG-WON OVERCAME HIS CRISIS,
BUT…

662
00:28:07,686 --> 00:28:08,920
INHALES

663
00:28:08,987 --> 00:28:10,955
NAM-NO TURNS INTO MR. ANXIETY

664
00:28:11,523 --> 00:28:14,325
HE BEGINS TO BREATHE HEAVILY

665
00:28:14,893 --> 00:28:17,395
He's working on the lamb chops now.

666
00:28:17,462 --> 00:28:19,831
What are you marinading the lamb chops in?
What did you use?

667
00:28:19,898 --> 00:28:22,967
-It's the smoky flavored oil.
-Flavored oil.

668
00:28:23,034 --> 00:28:24,569
That and cayenne pepper.

669
00:28:24,636 --> 00:28:26,805
-Cayenne pepper to add spice.
-It'll taste spicy.

670
00:28:26,871 --> 00:28:29,340
Nam-no doesn't miss this chance.

671
00:28:31,076 --> 00:28:34,045
He's using kimchi,
but it doesn't seem like Korean cuisine.

672
00:28:34,112 --> 00:28:36,948
-It's a different style.
-Right.

673
00:28:37,515 --> 00:28:39,317
2. COOK NAENGMYEON NOODLES
IN BOILING WATER

674
00:28:39,384 --> 00:28:41,419
TIMER ON

675
00:28:41,986 --> 00:28:44,022
HE BOILS THE BONE BROTH

676
00:28:44,622 --> 00:28:46,024
CLEANS UP IN THE MEANWHILE

677
00:28:46,091 --> 00:28:50,295
He went through so much trouble
trying to make that apple ring.

678
00:28:50,361 --> 00:28:52,097
I hope that's useful.

679
00:28:52,163 --> 00:28:54,165
But you shouldn't have cut it.

680
00:28:54,232 --> 00:28:56,568
-It's a shame that he cut it off.
-He did, right?

681
00:28:56,634 --> 00:28:59,070
He looks heartbroken.

682
00:28:59,137 --> 00:29:01,606
-We can't stitch it up for him.
-No.

683
00:29:01,673 --> 00:29:04,075
-If I had thread on me, I'd love to.
-Yes.

684
00:29:04,142 --> 00:29:06,911
-It'll make a gap if he cooks with it.
-Tell me about it!

685
00:29:06,978 --> 00:29:09,080
-My gosh.
-What is he going to do?

686
00:29:09,147 --> 00:29:11,015
-They're teasing him.
-It's too…

687
00:29:11,082 --> 00:29:12,984
-They attack him mentally.
-It's so funny.

688
00:29:13,585 --> 00:29:15,019
SWOOSH(?)

689
00:29:15,086 --> 00:29:17,922
BUT HE DOESN'T FORGET
HIS GOOD VIBES MOMENT

690
00:29:18,490 --> 00:29:21,126
3. SCOOP OUT COOKED NOODLES
AND COOL IN ICED WATER

691
00:29:21,693 --> 00:29:24,095
HE TAKES THE BONE BROTH
OFF THE HEAT

692
00:29:24,662 --> 00:29:26,998
AND ADDS WHITE KIMCHI WATER

693
00:29:27,599 --> 00:29:29,734
He's adding a lot of vinegar.

694
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:31,035
-Vinegar.
-What's that?

695
