HE HAS TO GET THE EGG GARNISH

924
00:39:25,029 --> 00:39:26,731
MUSHY

925
00:39:27,431 --> 00:39:30,067
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

926
00:39:30,134 --> 00:39:31,135
It's an accident!

927
00:39:31,202 --> 00:39:33,104
Oh, no.

928
00:39:33,671 --> 00:39:36,107
-It didn't work!
-Oh, no.

929
00:39:36,173 --> 00:39:39,009
It's an accident!

930
00:39:39,076 --> 00:39:42,313
What just happened?
There's been an accident with the egg.

931
00:39:42,380 --> 00:39:44,682
An accident with the egg.
Don't you need this?

932
00:39:44,749 --> 00:39:45,983
-Fifty seconds.
-Fifty seconds.

933
00:39:46,050 --> 00:39:48,753
-Turn it around.
-No, it's not going to work.

934
00:39:48,819 --> 00:39:49,820
ADDING SALT

935
00:39:50,955 --> 00:39:53,657
HUFFING

936
00:39:54,959 --> 00:39:57,762
Nam-no, your dish looks nice.

937
00:39:57,828 --> 00:39:59,196
Cabbage.

938
00:39:59,263 --> 00:40:02,032
If the lamb chops turn out tasty,
he'll probably win.

939
00:40:02,099 --> 00:40:05,102
-Thirty seconds.
-He's serving. Thirty seconds.

940
00:40:05,836 --> 00:40:09,507
JONG-WON FINALLY GETS
HIS EGG GARNISH

941
00:40:09,573 --> 00:40:10,775
It worked.

942
00:40:10,841 --> 00:40:13,744
-You need to cut the egg garnish.
-Thirty seconds.

943
00:40:14,578 --> 00:40:17,047
-Thirty seconds.
-Thirty seconds.

944
00:40:17,114 --> 00:40:18,382
Thirty seconds.

945
00:40:18,449 --> 00:40:20,384
Things are getting busy.

946
00:40:20,451 --> 00:40:23,521
Jong-won wasn't doing so well
starting with the apple, and now the egg.

947
00:40:23,587 --> 00:40:26,157
-Wait, what about the <i>naengmyeon</i>?
-20 seconds left!

948
00:40:26,223 --> 00:40:28,692
-The <i>naengmyeon</i>! The broth!
-The broth!

949
00:40:29,393 --> 00:40:32,696
HE CONTINUES HIS DELICATE PROCESS
AMIDST CHAOS

950
00:40:32,763 --> 00:40:33,831
-He threw it out.
-The broth!

951
00:40:33,898 --> 00:40:36,233
-Does he have the broth?
-He brought it out.

952
00:40:36,300 --> 00:40:37,768
You have ten seconds.

953
00:40:37,835 --> 00:40:39,136
Who'll finish first?

954
00:40:39,203 --> 00:40:41,672
You have ten seconds. Who'll finish first?

955
00:40:41,739 --> 00:40:44,208
HE TOPS THE LAMB CHOPS
WITH WOOD EARS

956
00:40:44,275 --> 00:40:45,776
-Eight, seven,
-Seven.

957
00:40:45,843 --> 00:40:48,746
-six, five, four…
-Oh, no.

958
00:40:49,313 --> 00:40:51,649
JONG-WON POURING THE BROTH

959
00:40:51,715 --> 00:40:54,485
VS NAM-NO POURING THE SAUCE

960
00:40:54,552 --> 00:40:56,554
WILL THEY FINISH
MAKING THE DISHES?

961
00:40:56,620 --> 00:40:59,356
-Three, two, one!
-Nam-no!

962
00:40:59,423 --> 00:41:02,726
Time's up.

963
00:41:03,527 --> 00:41:07,231
-That was crazy. It was real.
-Right? That was insane.

964
00:41:07,998 --> 00:41:09,300
TWO DIFFERENT KIMCHI DISHES
ARE READY

965
00:41:09,366 --> 00:41:10,968
It's so different.

966
00:41:11,702 --> 00:41:13,170
-Be careful.
-Time really flies.

967
00:41:13,237 --> 00:41:15,239
Right? Time really flew by.

968
00:41:15,306 --> 00:41:18,008
A lot has happened in the last 15 minutes.

969
00:41:18,075 --> 00:41:19,810
I want to check something with you.

970
00:41:19,877 --> 00:41:21,378
It's about the apple.

971
00:41:21,445 --> 00:41:22,980
-Stop it.
-Come on.

972
00:41:23,047 --> 00:41:25,950
-Cut it out with the apple.
-I still have to ask.

973
00:41:26,984 --> 00:41:28,586
There's something I want to say.

974
00:41:28,652 --> 00:41:30,521
I was going to cut it from the start,

975
00:41:30,588 --> 00:41:34,058
but it got cut automatically
and made it easier for me.

976
00:41:34,124 --> 00:41:35,426
Right?

977
00:41:35,493 --> 00:41:38,362
-I'm glad. I thought it was a ring.
-So, it wasn't a ring?

978
00:41:38,429 --> 00:41:40,931
I wasn't going to say anything,
but you're a good liar, aren't you?

979
00:41:42,166 --> 00:41:43,267
Seriously.

980
00:41:43,334 --> 00:41:45,269
-Were you satisfied as the fridge owner?
-Yes.

981
00:41:45,336 --> 00:41:48,038
I realized how short 15 minutes could be.

982
00:41:48,105 --> 00:41:49,807
It was probably hard for them,

983
00:41:49,874 --> 00:41:52,309
-but I had fun watching.
-True.

984
00:41:53,410 --> 00:41:56,814
MUKEUNJI SALAD
ON TOP OF RATATOUILLE

985
00:41:57,648 --> 00:42:01,752
A MIX OF KIMCHI DRESSING
AND LAMB CHOPS

986
00:42:02,853 --> 00:42:06,857
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
KIMCHI STREET FIGHT

987
00:42:07,424 --> 00:42:10,528
-I wanted to ring the bell later.
-Why?

988
00:42:10,594 --> 00:42:14,398
Because it's really delicious
to eat <i>naengmyeon</i> after meat.

989
00:42:14,465 --> 00:42:15,666
IT'S THE BEST

990
00:42:15,733 --> 00:42:18,569
-It'll make it more delicious.
-Yes, right.

991
00:42:18,636 --> 00:42:22,573
-It could've been Chef Jong-won's scheme.
-He must've ended later on purpose.

992
00:42:22,640 --> 00:42:24,441
I believe it was planned.

993
00:42:24,508 --> 00:42:27,044
So there's kimchi inside, right?

994
00:42:27,111 --> 00:42:30,347
There's ratatouille
made with zucchini and enoki mushroom.

995
00:42:30,414 --> 00:42:31,682
It's just vegetable stir-fry.

996
00:42:31,749 --> 00:42:35,219
-You used pepper leaves too, right?
-Yes, I did.

997
00:42:35,853 --> 00:42:39,390
And you said
the lamb chops smelled a little.

998
00:42:39,456 --> 00:42:42,226
-Yes, a little.
-I hope that's gone by now.

999
00:42:42,293 --> 00:42:44,495
Kimchi Street Fight.

1000
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:49,767
Will this dish be a worthy opponent
to start a street fight against Jong-won?

1001
00:42:49,833 --> 00:42:51,435
The toughness is important too.

1002
00:42:51,502 --> 00:42:54,438
-It's perfectly grilled.
-Is it?

1003
00:42:54,505 --> 00:42:56,307
That's an important point.
The lamb chops are a success.

1004
00:42:56,373 --> 00:42:57,541
It shouldn't be tough.

1005
00:42:57,608 --> 00:43:01,078
And he successfully managed
to get rid of the smell.

1006
00:43:01,145 --> 00:43:03,914
-It tastes great to me.
-He got rid of that distinct smell.

1007
00:43:03,981 --> 00:43:06,283
Let me try some more veggies.

1008
00:43:06,350 --> 00:43:09,019
He was supposed to cook with kimchi,

1009
00:43:09,086 --> 00:43:11,889
so it has to have a good presence.

1010
00:43:11,956 --> 00:43:13,857
-Otherwise, it's meaningless.
-That can't be the case.

1011
00:43:13,924 --> 00:43:15,893
I tried the part with <i>mukeunji</i>,

1012
00:43:15,960 --> 00:43:20,497
and I can taste that tangy
and sour flavor.

1013
00:43:21,332 --> 00:43:25,069
-But it disappears shortly after?
-Yes.

1014
00:43:25,135 --> 00:43:27,871
But it's like a supporting role
that stays alive until the end.

1015
00:43:27,938 --> 00:43:30,207
-Does it survive?
-It does.

1016
00:43:30,274 --> 00:43:32,443
As it should.
This is supposed to be a kimchi dish.

1017
00:43:33,344 --> 00:43:35,312
Put it on the cabbage. Yes.

1018
00:43:35,379 --> 00:43:37,047
-Okay.
-All right.

1019
00:43:37,114 --> 00:43:41,018
The wood ear should have a similar texture
to your favorite food, seaweed stem.

1020
00:43:41,085 --> 00:43:43,487
She said she liked seaweed stem.

1021
00:43:43,554 --> 00:43:46,357
I can already tell by her face.

1022
00:43:47,324 --> 00:43:48,759
So? Yes?

1023
00:43:48,826 --> 00:43:50,661
-It's good.
-It is?

1024
00:43:50,728 --> 00:43:53,464
What do you like about it?

1025
00:43:53,530 --> 00:43:55,432
When he used pepper leaves,

1026
00:43:55,499 --> 00:43:59,036
I wondered what it would be like
to add that to his mix.

1027
00:43:59,103 --> 00:44:01,839
But I can taste the flavor
of every single ingredient.

1028
00:44:01,905 --> 00:44:05,376
And I also love
the texture of the zucchini.

1029
00:44:05,442 --> 00:44:07,745
It's the kind of texture I love.

1030
00:44:07,811 --> 00:44:10,681
-The zucchini, huh? Right.
-Yes, how it's cooked.

1031
00:44:11,849 --> 00:44:15,819
-Chef Jong-won's dish is…
-The noodles are getting soggy.

1032
00:44:15,886 --> 00:44:18,188
-Let me have another bite.
-She takes another bite.

1033
00:44:18,255 --> 00:44:19,556
You can eat some more after that.

1034
00:44:19,623 --> 00:44:21,458
It looks like the lamb chops
are still rare.

1035
00:44:21,525 --> 00:44:26,463
I thought it was undercooked,
but it's cooked perfectly to my taste.

1036
00:44:26,530 --> 00:44:29,066
-Right? Is it perfect?
-Yes, it's great.

1037
00:44:29,133 --> 00:44:34,138
And the next dish is
Chef Jong-won's Kimchi Fine Da-heening.

1038
00:44:34,204 --> 00:44:37,808
COLORFUL TOPPINGS
IN AN APPLE RING WRAPPED IN KIMCHI

1039
00:44:38,575 --> 00:44:42,312
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
KIMCHI FINE DA-HEENING

1040
00:44:42,379 --> 00:44:43,947
-How do I eat this?
-Spread the noodles a little

1041
00:44:44,014 --> 00:44:46,150
before you try the broth.

1042
00:44:46,216 --> 00:44:47,384
-Spread the noodles.
-Spread them?

1043
00:44:47,451 --> 00:44:49,586
Sung-ju said <i>geotjeori </i>was too salty,

1044
00:44:49,653 --> 00:44:52,423
but the <i>geotjeori </i>seasoning
needs to seep into the broth.

1045
00:44:52,489 --> 00:44:54,224
That was why you made it salty.

1046
00:44:54,291 --> 00:44:57,861
He cut those vegetables
by measuring it with a ruler.

1047
00:44:57,928 --> 00:45:01,532
You could've have loosened up the noodles
if the apple was still in a ring.

1048
00:45:01,598 --> 00:45:03,634
-You're right.
-Everything was planned.

1049
00:45:03,701 --> 00:45:06,437
-It really was planned.
-She had to loosen it up.

1050
00:45:06,503 --> 00:45:08,739
She tore it apart.

1051
00:45:08,806 --> 00:45:09,840
That's a good portion.

1052
00:45:09,907 --> 00:45:12,309
-Yes, it is.
-I wonder if it's seasoned well.

1053
00:45:12,376 --> 00:45:15,379
Try the broth and the noodles.

1054
00:45:15,446 --> 00:45:16,447
She takes a bite.

1055
00:45:16,513 --> 00:45:18,315
A BIG BITE

1056
00:45:26,790 --> 00:45:29,593
She made that flirting face from earlier.
"Da-hee."

1057
00:45:29,660 --> 00:45:31,929
Head turns, then the eyes.

1058
00:45:31,995 --> 00:45:33,897
-Yes.
-She made that face.

1059
00:45:33,964 --> 00:45:35,999
-She looked at him like that.
-Yes.

1060
00:45:36,066 --> 00:45:37,568
Was she captivated?

1061
00:45:37,634 --> 00:45:40,738
-Flirting.
-What's wrong? Hey.

1062
00:45:40,804 --> 00:45:41,805
Look at her face.

1063
00:45:41,872 --> 00:45:43,807
-What is this?
-It must have an unexpected taste.

1064
00:45:44,508 --> 00:45:46,844
I guess it doesn't taste
like what we imagined.

1065
00:45:46,910 --> 00:45:49,947
It must have a great balance
when it came together.

1066
00:45:50,013 --> 00:45:52,816
-Yes, I was surprised.
-When it comes together?

1067
00:45:52,883 --> 00:45:55,285
There's a reason why
you made the <i>geotjeori</i> salty.

1068
00:45:55,352 --> 00:45:58,288
The <i>jokbal</i> doesn't taste like <i>jokbal</i>.

1069
00:45:58,355 --> 00:46:02,092
It tastes very exquisite,
unlike that pack of instant <i>jokbal</i>.

1070
00:46:02,159 --> 00:46:05,662
You know how ready-made food
has a distinct smell? Is it still there?

1071
00:46:05,729 --> 00:46:07,364
-No, not at all.
-Right?

1072
00:46:07,431 --> 00:46:09,633
-He boiled it. Right.
-He boiled it.

1073
00:46:09,700 --> 00:46:11,902
He boiled it and unseasoned it.

1074
00:46:11,969 --> 00:46:14,037
-He took out the flavor.
-It has a strong flavor.

1075
00:46:14,104 --> 00:46:17,674
His dish is scientific.

1076
00:46:18,308 --> 00:46:20,043
I knew it'd be the case
when he pulled out a ruler.

1077
00:46:21,311 --> 00:46:22,513
-But you know…
-Yes?

1078
00:46:22,579 --> 00:46:27,084
-…the apple is a game-changer.
-It needs it, huh?

1079
00:46:27,151 --> 00:46:28,152
It tastes so good.

1080
00:46:28,218 --> 00:46:31,188
This is among one of the best cold dishes

1081
00:46:31,255 --> 00:46:34,358
-I have ever had in my life.
-I see.

1082
00:46:34,424 --> 00:46:37,995
He laid out kimchi slices
on top of the apple wall.

1083
00:46:38,061 --> 00:46:40,297
It's like he hung up laundry.

1084
00:46:40,364 --> 00:46:43,267
It's on top of the apple wall
like he hung up laundry.

1085
00:46:43,333 --> 00:46:46,103
I cut up the apple and the kimchi,

1086
00:46:46,170 --> 00:46:48,772
-then topped it with everything else.
-You did?

1087
00:46:48,839 --> 00:46:52,676
-And it's absolutely delicious.
-I see.

1088
00:46:52,743 --> 00:46:56,914
This kimchi plays a great part
and makes great harmony with everything.

1089
00:46:56,980 --> 00:46:58,782
-This one too?
-It goes well together.

1090
00:46:58,849 --> 00:47:02,986
Okay. Chef Nam-no's Kimchi Street Fight.
Let's try it too.

1091
00:47:03,053 --> 00:47:04,688
Try some, DEX.

1092
00:47:06,456 --> 00:47:09,526
DA-HEE, THE GOURMET,
TAKES ANOTHER BITE

1093
00:47:10,093 --> 00:47:11,094
The <i>mukeunji…</i>

1094
00:47:12,196 --> 00:47:13,931
hits me right on the inside.

1095
00:47:13,997 --> 00:47:15,799
This is such an unusual combination.

1096
00:47:15,866 --> 00:47:20,871
Most places serve lamb chops
with thick and heavy sauce,

1097
00:47:20,938 --> 00:47:24,408
but this was made with kimchi.

1098
00:47:24,474 --> 00:47:28,979
So it's very light and refreshing.

1099
00:47:29,046 --> 00:47:32,683
But there could be someone
who's as sensitive to smell as I am.

1100
00:47:32,749 --> 00:47:35,152
Since this is a mix of the lamb smell
and the sourness of kimchi,

1101
00:47:35,219 --> 00:47:36,954
it brings out the lamb smell even more.

1102
00:47:37,020 --> 00:47:40,958
It feels like there's a big statement
coming from the lamb.

1103
00:47:41,024 --> 00:47:43,927
-So people will either love it or hate it.
-He's very honest.

1104
00:47:43,994 --> 00:47:45,996
I thought the kimchi flavor
would be lacking, but it was strong.

1105
00:47:46,063 --> 00:47:49,266
-I thought it went well with the order.
-All right.

1106
00:47:49,333 --> 00:47:52,970
Next, Kimchi Fine Da-heening.

1107
00:47:53,036 --> 00:47:56,273
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
KIMCHI FINE DA-HEENING

1108
00:47:56,340 --> 00:47:58,041
The <i>jokbal </i>adds a nice twist.

1109
00:47:58,809 --> 00:48:01,178
This is what came to mind
as soon as I had a bite.

1110
00:48:01,245 --> 00:48:05,949
It's like seeing the supermarket
during a big sale,

1111
00:48:06,016 --> 00:48:09,987
with people flocking everywhere.

1112
00:48:10,053 --> 00:48:13,190
It was like fireworks of different flavors
in my mouth.

1113
00:48:13,257 --> 00:48:15,259
The chair of the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance.

1114
00:48:15,325 --> 00:48:17,361
I don't want to admit this,

1115
00:48:17,427 --> 00:48:20,497
but it had a great balance
and wonderful flavors.

1116
00:48:20,564 --> 00:48:24,067
And especially so
when it comes to the texture

1117
00:48:24,134 --> 00:48:26,770
because the noodles came together
with the zucchini and everything.

1118
00:48:26,837 --> 00:48:29,006
-It wasn't too strong.
-It was intriguing.

1119
00:48:29,072 --> 00:48:32,643
-Does it taste delicious like this?
-That's right.

1120
00:48:32,709 --> 00:48:35,078
Enough is enough.

1121
00:48:35,145 --> 00:48:37,648
-It was an interesting dish.
-An interesting dish.

1122
00:48:37,714 --> 00:48:41,084
-It's now your turn to make a choice.
-Okay.

1123
00:48:41,151 --> 00:48:45,188
Which one of these dishes
captured Da-hee's palate more?

1124
00:48:45,255 --> 00:48:48,458
Which one was more suitable
to the order you made?

1125
00:48:48,525 --> 00:48:50,727
Which one did you like better?

1126
00:48:50,794 --> 00:48:52,362
KIMCHI FINE DA-HEENING

1127
00:48:52,429 --> 00:48:53,964
-I liked this one better.
-Because of the mild flavor?

1128
00:48:54,631 --> 00:48:56,066
Nothing else is important.

1129
00:48:56,133 --> 00:48:57,734
Let me say something
before she makes her choice.

1130
00:48:57,801 --> 00:49:00,604
I saw these two talking.
Which one did Chef Kang-rok pick?

1131
00:49:00,671 --> 00:49:02,706
-I asked him.
-Okay. Which one did you choose?

1132
00:49:02,773 --> 00:49:06,276
-Chef Kang-rok?
-Yes, well. This one. The <i>naengmyeon</i>.

1133
00:49:06,343 --> 00:49:08,512
I see. Son Jong-won.

1134
00:49:08,578 --> 00:49:10,013
Do you agree?

1135
00:49:10,080 --> 00:49:13,150
I personally don't like
Pyongyang-style naengmyeon.

1136
00:49:13,216 --> 00:49:16,053
I'll cast my vote for the lamb chops.

1137
00:49:16,119 --> 00:49:17,888
-They went separate ways.
-Different opinions.

1138
00:49:17,955 --> 00:49:21,124
Let's find out
which one Da-hee likes better!

1139
00:49:21,725 --> 00:49:23,927
-Kimchi dish to Paradise.
-This is nerve-racking.

1140
00:49:23,994 --> 00:49:28,165
Who'll go to Paradise
between Nam-no and Jong-won?

1141
00:49:28,231 --> 00:49:30,200
Will it be Nam-no
with one win and one loss?

1142
00:49:30,267 --> 00:49:32,202
Or two wins and one loss, Son Jong-won?

1143
00:49:32,269 --> 00:49:34,871
Who did Da-hee choose?

1144
00:49:35,872 --> 00:49:37,741
-The winner is…
-The winner is…

1145
00:49:37,808 --> 00:49:39,710
-The winner is…
-The winner is…

1146
00:49:41,812 --> 00:49:42,946
Son Jong-won!

1147
00:49:43,013 --> 00:49:44,848
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
KIMCHI FINE DA-HEENING WINS

1148
00:49:44,915 --> 00:49:49,386
Son Jong-won! Chef Good Vibes wins.

1149
00:49:49,886 --> 00:49:51,822
The Anti-Good Vibes Alliance fails.

1150
00:49:53,991 --> 00:49:55,859
Was there a difference? How was it?

1151
00:49:55,926 --> 00:49:59,229
I saw the ingredients
before they began to cook.

1152
00:49:59,296 --> 00:50:01,198
He began to mix vinegar
into the bone broth

1153
00:50:01,264 --> 00:50:04,868
and then used an apple out,
so everything was just unexpected.

1154
00:50:04,935 --> 00:50:08,238
So I thought
I wouldn't enjoy his dish very much.

1155
00:50:08,305 --> 00:50:13,710
But all my expectations came crashing down
as soon as I had a bite.

1156
00:50:13,777 --> 00:50:17,881
I realized how important balance is
while eating this.

1157
00:50:17,948 --> 00:50:20,484
-Yes.
-I felt it.

1158
00:50:20,550 --> 00:50:21,885
-It was delicious.
-Yes.

1159
00:50:21,952 --> 00:50:25,422
Da-hee, please put a star
on Chef Jong-won!

1160
00:50:25,489 --> 00:50:26,823
Congratulations.

1161
00:50:26,890 --> 00:50:28,058
Chef Jong-won wins.

1162
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:32,295
He fought against
the Anti-Good Vibes Alliance

1163
00:50:32,362 --> 00:50:33,997
and takes his third win.

1164
00:50:34,064 --> 00:50:35,732
-Thank you.
-Congratulations.

1165
00:50:35,799 --> 00:50:37,367
HE GETS THREE STARS
AND CONTINUES HIS WINNING STREAK

1166
00:50:37,868 --> 00:50:41,872
The second round
with Da-hee's ingredients.

1167
00:50:41,938 --> 00:50:46,076
<i>-First flavors are always so hard</i>
<i>-Always so hard</i>

1168
00:50:47,577 --> 00:50:50,981
I just showed you the dance
because you thought little of me before.

1169
00:50:51,048 --> 00:50:52,916
I know this.

1170
00:50:52,983 --> 00:50:54,384
IT'S HARD FOR ME TOO

1171
00:50:54,451 --> 00:50:59,256
This is the first encounter
for these two chefs.

1172
00:50:59,322 --> 00:51:02,092
Another famous chef of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

1173
00:51:02,159 --> 00:51:06,530
Mr. Slow, who's okay with his speed,
Chef Choi Kang-rok

1174
00:51:06,596 --> 00:51:11,501
is up against Show-off Chef,
Choi Hyun-suk, for the first time.

1175
00:51:11,568 --> 00:51:13,070
It's a match between
the chef with the most wins

1176
00:51:13,136 --> 00:51:15,238
and the chef with the most losses.

1177
00:51:15,305 --> 00:51:16,540
Five wins versus five losses.

1178
00:51:16,606 --> 00:51:19,309
You must feel a lot of burden
to fight against an undefeated chef,

1179
00:51:19,376 --> 00:51:21,478
-but it'll be huge if you win.
-That's true.

1180
00:51:21,545 --> 00:51:24,214
-It'll make the news.
-That's right.

1181
00:51:24,281 --> 00:51:27,751
People will talk about
how Kang-rok defeated Hyun-suk.

1182
00:51:27,818 --> 00:51:30,320
Chef Hyun-suk asked for this favor.

1183
00:51:30,387 --> 00:51:31,521
-He asked for a favor?
-Yes.

1184
00:51:31,588 --> 00:51:34,558
He wanted to look into Chef Rok's eyes
before they began.

1185
00:51:35,559 --> 00:51:36,560
What do you mean?

1186
00:51:36,626 --> 00:51:37,928
-Is it a face-off?
-Yes.

1187
00:51:37,994 --> 00:51:39,396
It's like this.

1188
00:51:42,132 --> 00:51:43,233
HEAD FIRST, EYES LATER…

1189
00:51:43,300 --> 00:51:45,869
Head first, then the eyes.

1190
00:51:45,936 --> 00:51:48,138
You can utilize
everything you learned today.

1191
00:51:48,205 --> 00:51:52,909
Look at this.
It's a battle between David and Goliath.

1192
00:51:52,976 --> 00:51:55,178
But David won against Goliath.

1193
00:51:55,245 --> 00:51:56,346
-Yes.
-That's true.

1194
00:51:56,413 --> 00:52:00,217
He's mixed up with ducks,
not realizing he's an eagle.

1195
00:52:00,283 --> 00:52:04,454
But if he just spread his wings and flies,
he can fly high as an eagle.

1196
00:52:04,521 --> 00:52:05,789
My gosh.

1197
00:52:05,856 --> 00:52:08,191
Why is that guy writing this down?

1198
00:52:08,825 --> 00:52:11,528
-Why are you writing it down?
-Did you like that comment?

1199
00:52:11,595 --> 00:52:13,964
-It was so moving.
-It was?

1200
00:52:14,030 --> 00:52:16,700
-Those two are perfect for each other.
-He's head over heels for him.

1201
00:52:16,766 --> 00:52:20,070
Anyway, the production crew
was quite worried about you, Da-hee.

1202
00:52:20,137 --> 00:52:21,538
-Me? Why?
-Right?

1203
00:52:21,605 --> 00:52:23,640
The first dishes…

1204
00:52:23,707 --> 00:52:25,342
-Let's take a ten-minute break.
-Okay.

1205
00:52:26,376 --> 00:52:28,078
SHE FIXES HER POSTURE

1206
00:52:28,145 --> 00:52:30,313
AND PICKS UP THE CHOPSTICKS AGAIN

1207
00:52:32,315 --> 00:52:33,984
TAKING ANOTHER BITE

1208
00:52:34,851 --> 00:52:36,887
I'll hit the slate. One, two, three.

1209
00:52:36,953 --> 00:52:39,489
SHE FOCUSES ON HER FOOD
EVEN WHEN A STAFF PASSES BY

1210
00:52:40,056 --> 00:52:42,626
HER EATING SHOW DOESN'T END

1211
00:52:42,692 --> 00:52:43,693
MMM

1212
00:52:45,829 --> 00:52:47,864
She's eating nonstop.
It must be really good.

1213
00:52:49,199 --> 00:52:50,834
AND SHE CONTINUED TO EAT…

1214
00:52:51,401 --> 00:52:53,570
-We heard you finished it.
-We heard you finished it all.

1215
00:52:53,637 --> 00:52:57,040
Yes, it was good, so I kept eating it,
but the production crew

1216
00:52:57,107 --> 00:52:59,943
told me to stop
because I still had to eat some more.

1217
00:53:00,010 --> 00:53:01,077
But it was so good.

1218
00:53:01,144 --> 00:53:03,980
-I hope you enjoy the next set of dishes.
-I will.

1219
00:53:04,047 --> 00:53:05,549
What will they make?

1220
00:53:06,383 --> 00:53:10,387
CHEF KANG-ROK'S INGREDIENTS:

1221
00:53:10,453 --> 00:53:14,324
CUTLASS FISH, REFINED RICE WINE

1222
00:53:14,391 --> 00:53:16,760
Chef Kang-rok, what are you making?

1223
00:53:16,826 --> 00:53:18,628
Today, I'll make

1224
00:53:18,695 --> 00:53:21,798
Lightly Braised Cutlass fish Over Rice.

1225
00:53:21,865 --> 00:53:23,800
-Cutlass fish?
-Cutlass fish?

1226
00:53:23,867 --> 00:53:26,836
Lightly Braised Cutlass fish Over Rice.
Will you braise something?

1227
00:53:26,903 --> 00:53:29,673
There are many different ways
to braise a dish.

1228
00:53:29,739 --> 00:53:34,010
I'll cover the fish with seasoning
and lightly braise it.

1229
00:53:34,077 --> 00:53:35,579
Is it like eel over rice?

1230
00:53:35,645 --> 00:53:38,281
It may be more delicious than that.

1231
00:53:38,348 --> 00:53:39,516
I see.

1232
00:53:41,251 --> 00:53:44,221
This is what I wanted to see
from Chef Kang-rok

1233
00:53:44,287 --> 00:53:45,755
when I said he could be an eagle.

1234
00:53:46,723 --> 00:53:48,592
-He's already an eagle.
-Is he?

1235
00:53:48,658 --> 00:53:52,362
But she said she liked meat
more than fish.

1236
00:53:52,429 --> 00:53:53,763
Do you like cutlass fish?

1237
00:53:54,564 --> 00:53:56,333
Cutlass fish. He'll braise it.

1238
00:53:56,399 --> 00:53:57,867
Well, I do eat it.

1239
00:53:57,934 --> 00:53:59,569
She does eat it.

1240
00:53:59,636 --> 00:54:02,339
This is bad. That was pretty significant.

1241
00:54:02,405 --> 00:54:03,773
I'm really curious.

1242
00:54:03,840 --> 00:54:07,210
-Was there a reason for picking that fish?
-Well…

1243
00:54:07,277 --> 00:54:10,947
If you have only this life to live,

1244
00:54:11,014 --> 00:54:12,782
would you eat cutlass fish?

1245
00:54:14,050 --> 00:54:16,486
ANSWERING THE QUESTION
WITH A QUESTION

1246
00:54:16,553 --> 00:54:20,156
-You've already had too much meat.
-You're right.

1247
00:54:20,223 --> 00:54:22,759
-The theme is "the first encounter."
-The first encounter.

1248
00:54:22,826 --> 00:54:26,563
I wanted to make this
a great first meeting for you two.

1249
00:54:26,630 --> 00:54:28,498
That's so fitting with the theme.

1250
00:54:29,432 --> 00:54:31,534
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:

1251
00:54:31,601 --> 00:54:33,703
OLIVE OIL, CHICKEN STOCK, SHIITAKE
ENOKI, ZUCCHINI, RAMYEON

1252
00:54:33,770 --> 00:54:35,272
Chef Hyun-suk is up against him.

1253
00:54:35,338 --> 00:54:36,840
What did you prepare?

1254
00:54:36,906 --> 00:54:39,676
Before I present today's dish…
Chef Sung-jun.

1255
00:54:39,743 --> 00:54:41,311
-Get ready to take notes.
-Yes, sir.

1256
00:54:42,245 --> 00:54:43,280
GOODNESS GRACIOUS…

1257
00:54:43,346 --> 00:54:44,581
He's doing it out in the open.

1258
00:54:44,648 --> 00:54:47,684
I may or may not be starting

1259
00:54:47,751 --> 00:54:49,653
yet another battle with myself.

1260
00:54:51,187 --> 00:54:53,256
EVERYONE'S TOLERANCE FOR
HIS CHEESY LINES SLOWLY DWINDLE

1261
00:54:53,323 --> 00:54:55,558
I get it, so tell us what it is.

1262
00:54:55,625 --> 00:54:58,161
My dish is called

1263
00:54:58,228 --> 00:55:00,764
Da-hee Hard Risotto.

1264
00:55:00,830 --> 00:55:03,366
-Da-hee Hard Risotto.
-Da-hee Hard Risotto.

1265
00:55:03,433 --> 00:55:06,936
There are many chefs who had a tough time
trying to make risotto here.

1266
00:55:07,003 --> 00:55:08,838
-Yes.
-That's the case.

1267
00:55:08,905 --> 00:55:11,975
But I guarantee that you've never seen
what I'm going to make today.

1268
00:55:12,042 --> 00:55:15,011
So this is a challenge for me too.

1269
00:55:15,078 --> 00:55:17,213
I'll make it happen
and capture your palate.

1270
00:55:18,114 --> 00:55:21,318
Is this a dish that all these chefs
have never seen before?

1271
00:55:21,384 --> 00:55:24,254
But a risotto is just a risotto.

1272
00:55:24,321 --> 00:55:26,489
Have you ever seen me make a cliché dish?

1273
00:55:27,857 --> 00:55:30,994
You're so brazen. It's unbelievable.

1274
00:55:31,061 --> 00:55:32,495
It's a new kind of risotto.

1275
00:55:32,562 --> 00:55:36,666
Now, let them begin their cook-off.

1276
00:55:37,834 --> 00:55:42,005
<i>-The first loss is so hard</i>
<i>-So hard</i>

1277
00:55:42,072 --> 00:55:44,708
The king of show-offs thinks once again,
it'll be hard to lose.

1278
00:55:44,774 --> 00:55:46,676
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

1279
00:55:46,743 --> 00:55:49,546
But Mr. Braise is here
to braise his arrogance down.

1280
00:55:49,612 --> 00:55:51,948
Chef Choi Kang-rok is up as well.

1281
00:55:52,015 --> 00:55:54,951
The first battle
between Mr. Show-off and Mr. Braise.

1282
00:55:55,018 --> 00:55:58,621
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1283
00:56:00,290 --> 00:56:02,225
Begin!

1284
00:56:02,792 --> 00:56:04,461
MR. BRAISE VS MR. SHOW-OFF

1285
00:56:04,527 --> 00:56:07,197
He begins with the cutlass fish.

1286
00:56:07,263 --> 00:56:10,100
-The cutlass fish.
-He's moving fast today.

1287
00:56:10,166 --> 00:56:12,335
The cutlass fish is in good condition.

1288
00:56:12,402 --> 00:56:14,304
I guess he's just using the flesh.

1289
00:56:14,371 --> 00:56:16,439
He'll leave out the bones.

1290
00:56:17,707 --> 00:56:20,577
He's making very neat fillets.

1291
00:56:21,578 --> 00:56:22,946
Shiitake.

1292
00:56:23,012 --> 00:56:25,749
Chef Hyun-suk starts with shiitake.

1293
00:56:25,815 --> 00:56:26,983
AND UP NEXT IS

1294
00:56:29,152 --> 00:56:32,155
-Is he using <i>ramyeon </i>soup base?
-<i>Ramyeon </i>soup base?

1295
00:56:32,222 --> 00:56:34,224
-Isn't that <i>ramyeon </i>soup base?
-It is.

1296
00:56:34,290 --> 00:56:36,393
It's kind of a cheap move
to use <i>ramyeon </i>soup base.

1297
00:56:36,459 --> 00:56:39,496
I haven't even used it
in the second season.

1298
00:56:39,562 --> 00:56:40,997
You're using <i>ramyeon </i>soup base?

1299
00:56:41,765 --> 00:56:43,032
2. MAKE BATTER WITH RAMYEON
SOUP BASE AND FRYING POWDER

1300
00:56:43,099 --> 00:56:44,367
-Let's see how he does this.
-He wants to win.

1301
00:56:44,434 --> 00:56:46,002
He really wants to win.

1302
00:56:46,069 --> 00:56:47,470
He's using it out in the open.

1303
00:56:47,537 --> 00:56:49,105
THIS TIME,
HE'S SPRAYING THE ENOKI?

1304
00:56:49,606 --> 00:56:50,974
What did he just spray?

1305
00:56:51,040 --> 00:56:52,342
He just sprayed something.

1306
00:56:52,409 --> 00:56:55,345
-He sprayed water to mix it with powder.
-Was it water?

1307
00:56:55,412 --> 00:56:57,180
-It's for frying powder.
-Right, I see.

1308
00:56:57,247 --> 00:57:00,750
He sprayed water to make it easier
for the frying powder to stick.

1309
00:57:00,817 --> 00:57:02,852
I see. I guess he'll fry those.

1310
00:57:02,919 --> 00:57:04,120
It's been a minute already?

1311
00:57:04,187 --> 00:57:06,689
-That's…
-I think he'll fry the mushroom.

1312
00:57:06,756 --> 00:57:09,292
But he should cook the rice first

1313
00:57:09,359 --> 00:57:11,661
-to make risotto in 15 minutes.
-I know.

1314
00:57:11,728 --> 00:57:14,898
It takes a while for the rice to cook
when you make risotto.

1315
00:57:15,465 --> 00:57:17,100
Did she even have rice?

1316
00:57:17,167 --> 00:57:21,104
IT'LL TAKE A WHILE
FOR HIM TO COOK THE RICE

1317
00:57:21,671 --> 00:57:23,807
BUT FIRST, FRIED ENOKI IS DONE

1318
00:57:24,474 --> 00:57:28,711
Chef Kang-rok is focused on
prepping the cutlass fish.

1319
00:57:28,778 --> 00:57:31,014
There can't be any bones in the fillets.

1320
00:57:31,080 --> 00:57:33,483
That fish requires a lot of work.

1321
00:57:33,550 --> 00:57:35,485
The cutlass fish…

1322
00:57:35,552 --> 00:57:40,623
But it won't be easy to braise
a thick fish fillet in this time.

1323
00:57:40,690 --> 00:57:44,427
-Chef Kang-rok gets faster over time.
-He does.

1324
00:57:44,494 --> 00:57:47,497
I've always been this fast.

1325
00:57:47,564 --> 00:57:48,631
FEELING CONFIDENT AFTER 3 MONTHS

1326
00:57:48,698 --> 00:57:50,433
He can even hear us!

1327
00:57:51,634 --> 00:57:55,138
He can even hear us!
Not only that, he can respond too!

1328
00:57:55,205 --> 00:57:58,074
-He never answered us before.
-He's showing growth!

1329
00:57:58,141 --> 00:57:59,576
-Yes.
-You must be used to it now.

1330
00:57:59,642 --> 00:58:01,211
-Yes, I am.
-He can talk back.

1331
00:58:01,778 --> 00:58:03,880
I can do that much.

1332
00:58:03,947 --> 00:58:05,215
You could always do this.

1333
00:58:05,281 --> 00:58:07,250
Why didn't we know until now?

1334
00:58:07,317 --> 00:58:10,119
HYUN-SUK GETS SOME FLOUR READY

1335
00:58:10,887 --> 00:58:12,755
5. MAKE DOUGH BY MIXING FLOUR AND
WATER WITH AN IMMERSION BLENDER

1336
00:58:12,822 --> 00:58:14,491
-I see.
-He's blending something.

1337
00:58:14,557 --> 00:58:16,259
-I think that's flour.
-He's making fresh pasta.

1338
00:58:16,326 --> 00:58:17,861
Fresh pasta?

1339
00:58:17,927 --> 00:58:20,597
But he needs to make risotto, not pasta.

1340
00:58:20,663 --> 00:58:22,465
I think he'll make grain-shaped pasta.

1341
00:58:22,532 --> 00:58:25,134
-I see, instead of using real rice?
-Really?

1342
00:58:25,201 --> 00:58:26,636
He's using fresh pasta.

1343
00:58:26,703 --> 00:58:29,706
But he'll have to make
every grain by hand.

1344
00:58:29,772 --> 00:58:31,007
-So tiny pieces?
-Yes.

1345
00:58:31,074 --> 00:58:33,443
-But rice grains are tiny.
-Yes, I have no idea.

1346
00:58:33,510 --> 00:58:34,511
You won't have enough time.

1347
00:58:34,577 --> 00:58:37,046
-I don't know if he'll have enough time.
-Will he?

1348
00:58:38,081 --> 00:58:39,849
How is he going to do this?

1349
00:58:40,583 --> 00:58:42,519
Are you really going for it?

1350
00:58:43,386 --> 00:58:44,487
He's doing it.

1351
00:58:44,554 --> 00:58:46,656
-He's already made the dough.
-I have a feeling

1352
00:58:46,723 --> 00:58:48,791
he'll make a thin layer and cut it out.

1353
00:58:48,858 --> 00:58:51,327
-That'll still take a long time.
-All right.

1354
00:58:51,394 --> 00:58:53,062
This is very important.

1355
00:58:53,129 --> 00:58:54,831
He just made pasta dough

1356
00:58:54,898 --> 00:58:59,903
to make rice grains with that dough.

1357
00:59:02,272 --> 00:59:03,273
He has begun.

1358
00:59:03,339 --> 00:59:04,574
No way.

1359
00:59:10,113 --> 00:59:11,948
You're doing this now?

1360
00:59:12,015 --> 00:59:13,816
It'll take you forever!

1361
00:59:13,883 --> 00:59:15,852
-This is just wrong.
-My gosh.

1362
00:59:15,919 --> 00:59:17,887
NO SECRETS,
IT'S THE TEXTBOOK WAY!

1363
00:59:17,954 --> 00:59:19,989
You're going to do this?

1364
00:59:20,056 --> 00:59:21,057
He's doing this now.

1365
00:59:21,124 --> 00:59:22,425
This is too much.

1366
00:59:22,492 --> 00:59:27,030
It's like how he used to make
the pasta noodles.

1367
00:59:27,096 --> 00:59:29,532
I don't think he'll have enough portion.

1368
00:59:29,599 --> 00:59:32,702
-She'll get two bites.
-Right?

1369
00:59:32,769 --> 00:59:34,037
And we need to try some too.

1370
00:59:34,103 --> 00:59:37,974
-This is…
-It's a nice try, though.

1371
00:59:38,041 --> 00:59:39,042
It's a bold move.

1372
00:59:39,108 --> 00:59:42,145
It's like something
made by a minority group.

1373
00:59:42,211 --> 00:59:44,948
Something they make at home.

1374
00:59:45,014 --> 00:59:49,786
He just made like 20 grains.

1375
00:59:49,852 --> 00:59:51,654
That's less than a spoon of rice.

1376
00:59:52,622 --> 00:59:54,857
We keep praising you,
and now you go ahead and do this?

1377
00:59:54,924 --> 00:59:56,092
He needs at least five minutes for that.

1378
00:59:56,159 --> 00:59:58,127
-He'll do it until the end.
-He can't do it.

1379
00:59:58,194 --> 00:59:59,195
Are you making a spoon of pasta?

1380
00:59:59,262 --> 01:00:01,297
It took him a minute
to make a spoonful.

1381
01:00:01,364 --> 01:00:03,399
Do you have to do this?

1382
01:00:04,667 --> 01:00:06,736
-Chef Hyun-suk!
-Don't talk to him.

1383
01:00:06,803 --> 01:00:08,237
Don't talk to him.

1384
01:00:08,304 --> 01:00:10,607
-Are you regretting this?
-What are you doing?

1385
01:00:10,673 --> 01:00:14,277
-That means the sizes will be different.
-That's right.

1386
01:00:14,344 --> 01:00:15,345
I think he's regretting it.

1387
01:00:15,411 --> 01:00:16,913
THANKS TO MR. SHOW-OFF
TAKING THE ATTENTION,

1388
01:00:17,480 --> 01:00:20,450
MR. BRAISE IS HAVING
THE MOST PEACEFUL TIME

1389
01:00:21,784 --> 01:00:23,319
SKIN ON THE FISH MEAT

1390
01:00:25,355 --> 01:00:26,723
COMPLETELY GONE

1391
01:00:26,789 --> 01:00:28,291
NEATLY PREPPED

1392
01:00:28,858 --> 01:00:32,261
HE QUIETLY DOES HIS BEST
AWAY FROM PEOPLE'S ATTENTION

1393
01:00:33,329 --> 01:00:38,368
2. TAKE THE SEEDS OUT OF
BITE-SIZE CHEONGYANG PEPPER PIECES

1394
01:00:38,935 --> 01:00:40,403
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, PREPPED

1395
01:00:41,137 --> 01:00:43,239
NEXT, PLASTERING CUTLASS FISH
WITH FLOUR

1396
01:00:43,940 --> 01:00:47,176
HE DOES IT CAREFULLY,
LIKE HE'S DRESSING A CHILD

1397
01:00:47,243 --> 01:00:52,882
Look at that. Chef Kang-rok
is done coating flour on the fish.

1398
01:00:52,949 --> 01:00:54,784
He prepped the fish neatly.

1399
01:00:54,851 --> 01:00:56,586
3. COAT CUTLASS FISH FILLETS
WITH FLOUR

1400
01:00:56,653 --> 01:00:58,187
Gosh.

1401
01:00:58,254 --> 01:00:59,255
The dough is…

1402
01:00:59,322 --> 01:01:01,424
The dough is too thick,
and it's hurting my hands.

1403
01:01:01,491 --> 01:01:02,558
I'm doomed.

1404
01:01:02,625 --> 01:01:04,060
Don't they look like rice puffs?

1405
01:01:04,994 --> 01:01:09,165
Chef Hyun-suk will be doing that
for the next five minutes.

1406
01:01:09,232 --> 01:01:10,233
Chef Kang-rok!

1407
01:01:10,299 --> 01:01:14,070
I hear cutlass fish scales
can smell a bit.

1408
01:01:14,137 --> 01:01:16,105
Cutlass fish doesn't have scales.

1409
01:01:16,172 --> 01:01:19,742
-I mean the white skin.
-Right.

1410
01:01:19,809 --> 01:01:21,010
BROKEN

1411
01:01:21,577 --> 01:01:22,679
HIS MULTITASKING FUNCTION IS LOST

1412
01:01:22,745 --> 01:01:24,947
-Turn the stove on first.
-Okay.

1413
01:01:26,149 --> 01:01:27,817
-It's rather fresh.
-It's fresh?

1414
01:01:27,884 --> 01:01:29,118
It's not so bad.

1415
01:01:30,753 --> 01:01:32,121
Gosh, my hands are numb.

1416
01:01:32,188 --> 01:01:34,490
Wait.

1417
01:01:34,557 --> 01:01:37,727
It's as if he's throwing away
eraser shavings.

1418
01:01:37,794 --> 01:01:39,162
-Eraser shavings.
-Like when we were in school.

1419
01:01:39,228 --> 01:01:40,430
Eraser shavings.

1420
01:01:40,496 --> 01:01:42,065
When you're nervous before a test,

1421
01:01:42,131 --> 01:01:44,167
you keep picking on the eraser.

1422
01:01:44,233 --> 01:01:46,869
-Yes, because you're nervous.
-Eraser shavings?

1423
01:01:46,936 --> 01:01:50,339
-It's like that.
-Mr. Show-off became Mr. Anxiety.

1424
01:01:50,406 --> 01:01:53,476
Is it just me,
or are the pieces getting bigger?

1425
01:01:53,543 --> 01:01:54,711
Please keep them in similar sizes.

1426
01:01:54,777 --> 01:01:56,646
The grains of rice we eat

1427
01:01:56,713 --> 01:01:58,481
all come in different sizes too.

1428
01:01:58,548 --> 01:02:01,884
It gets a little bigger when it's cooked.

1429
01:02:01,951 --> 01:02:04,787
You have a little less than
nine minutes left.

1430
01:02:04,854 --> 01:02:06,789
Why is he doing that?

1431
01:02:06,856 --> 01:02:09,325
-Just use pasta.
-I'm sure he has a reason.

1432
01:02:09,392 --> 01:02:10,393
Wait.

1433
01:02:10,993 --> 01:02:12,729
Da-hee wants a new experience.

1434
01:02:12,795 --> 01:02:15,865
Why are you all complaining?

1435
01:02:15,932 --> 01:02:17,467
WAS THAT THE REASON?

1436
01:02:17,533 --> 01:02:21,370
-So that's why.
-My thumb and index finger are gone.

1437
01:02:21,437 --> 01:02:23,239
Hey, Da-hee.

1438
01:02:23,306 --> 01:02:25,108
How's this new experience?

1439
01:02:25,174 --> 01:02:27,443
As I watch him, I'm starting to feel…

1440
01:02:27,510 --> 01:02:28,711
-Do you feel bad?
-Yes.

1441
01:02:28,778 --> 01:02:31,214
Your two fingers will end up bleeding.

1442
01:02:31,280 --> 01:02:33,716
-This is so awful.
-You can't pick up anything from now on.

1443
01:02:33,783 --> 01:02:34,784
Oh, no.

1444
01:02:34,851 --> 01:02:37,186
His hands will feel numb soon.

1445
01:02:37,253 --> 01:02:39,555
-He'll end up losing his skin.
-They'll stick together.

1446
01:02:39,622 --> 01:02:41,791
What if he loses his own flesh?

1447
01:02:41,858 --> 01:02:42,959
Hey, Poong!

1448
01:02:43,025 --> 01:02:44,994
If you're free, come and do this.

1449
01:02:45,061 --> 01:02:47,163
-Do you need help?
-No, I got it.

1450
01:02:47,230 --> 01:02:50,032
Kang-rok will win
if he makes a decent dish.

1451
01:02:50,099 --> 01:02:53,603
All he needs to do is make sure
it doesn't smell fishy.

1452
01:02:54,170 --> 01:02:56,806
CUTLASS FISH GOES IN

1453
01:02:56,873 --> 01:02:59,842
Will you fry it first,
then grill it again?

1454
01:02:59,909 --> 01:03:03,479
Yes, he'll grill it first,
then braise it with the sauce.

1455
01:03:03,546 --> 01:03:04,914
He'll grill it first.

1456
01:03:04,981 --> 01:03:07,416
He doesn't have enough time,
so he can't just braise it.

1457
01:03:07,483 --> 01:03:10,353
-Kang-rok.
-He's grilling it over low heat.

1458
01:03:10,419 --> 01:03:13,189
-It won't take long to braise it.
-It won't?

1459
01:03:13,256 --> 01:03:14,557
I hope he does it quickly.

1460
01:03:14,624 --> 01:03:15,625
GETS THE PAN READY

1461
01:03:15,691 --> 01:03:18,161
REFINED RICE WINE, COOKING WINE,
SOY SAUCE

1462
01:03:18,728 --> 01:03:20,797
AND SUGAR!

1463
01:03:21,898 --> 01:03:23,299
I'M RIGHT HERE

1464
01:03:23,366 --> 01:03:24,801
OH, RIGHT

1465
01:03:24,867 --> 01:03:26,869
Did you just add soy sauce and sugar?

1466
01:03:26,936 --> 01:03:29,071
Yes, soy sauce, sugar,
cooking wine, and refined rice wine.

1467
01:03:30,306 --> 01:03:31,507
So that's the sauce.

1468
01:03:31,574 --> 01:03:34,911
They'll both fight against time.

1469
01:03:34,977 --> 01:03:37,380
Kang-rok needs to grill them,
then braise them.

1470
01:03:37,446 --> 01:03:38,681
He's warming up instant rice.

1471
01:03:38,748 --> 01:03:39,749
OPENING? CLOSING?

1472
01:03:39,816 --> 01:03:41,117
HE OPENED IT!

1473
01:03:42,718 --> 01:03:44,187
MAKING GRAINS FOR 5 MINUTES!

1474
01:03:44,253 --> 01:03:48,124
That's a perfect size for your goldfish
when you feed them.

1475
01:03:48,191 --> 01:03:49,392
Goldfish?

1476
01:03:49,458 --> 01:03:51,828
-I mean…
-My fingers hurt.

1477
01:03:52,395 --> 01:03:54,263
RICE GRAIN INFERNO

1478
01:03:55,097 --> 01:03:57,033
-Yes, however,
-What's with him today?

1479
01:03:57,099 --> 01:03:59,635
Da-hee is watching all your effort.

1480
01:03:59,702 --> 01:04:01,437
But I'm starting to worry

1481
01:04:01,504 --> 01:04:03,973
-that he won't be able to finish cooking.
-The dish?

1482
01:04:04,040 --> 01:04:05,107
-In that case…
-He has seven minutes left.

1483
01:04:05,174 --> 01:04:06,375
…you'll eat raw rice.

1484
01:04:06,442 --> 01:04:09,278
-No, raw flour dough.
-It's made with flour.

1485
01:04:09,345 --> 01:04:11,981
-You'll eat raw flour.
-You'll eat raw flour.

1486
01:04:12,048 --> 01:04:14,283
Is everything going well for you,
Chef Kang-rok?

1487
01:04:15,051 --> 01:04:17,320
Yes, I think it's going well.

1488
01:04:17,386 --> 01:04:18,387
A bit of salt.

1489
01:04:19,121 --> 01:04:21,324
This gives Kang-rok the advantage.

1490
01:04:21,390 --> 01:04:24,126
-They kind of look like eel.
-Right.

1491
01:04:24,193 --> 01:04:26,729
It'll taste delicious
when you braise it in the sauce.

1492
01:04:27,396 --> 01:04:30,566
Chef Hyun-suk's hands
are starting to tremble.

1493
01:04:30,633 --> 01:04:33,970
Chef Hyun-suk,
the pieces are getting larger.

1494
01:04:34,036 --> 01:04:35,171
-What will he do now?
-It's snowballing.

1495
01:04:35,238 --> 01:04:37,840
-They're bigger.
-He's in a trance.

1496
01:04:37,907 --> 01:04:41,043
Oh, dear,
you lost a nail on your left hand.

1497
01:04:41,110 --> 01:04:42,945
IT'S FUN TO TEASE HIM

1498
01:04:43,012 --> 01:04:45,514
I think you lost a nail
on your left index finger.

1499
01:04:46,616 --> 01:04:48,551
You have five minutes left.

1500
01:04:48,618 --> 01:04:49,619
-Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

1501
01:04:49,685 --> 01:04:51,287
-Please go out on the field.
-All right.

1502
01:04:51,354 --> 01:04:53,856
-There's nothing for the host to see.
-I know.

1503
01:04:53,923 --> 01:04:56,659
You spent all your time on this,
and you have less than five minutes.

1504
01:04:57,226 --> 01:05:00,229
-He had fried some enoki earlier.
-Right.

1505
01:05:00,296 --> 01:05:02,064
Okay, let me take a look and see

1506
01:05:02,131 --> 01:05:04,267
-how many spoons he made so far.
-Oh, dear.

1507
01:05:04,333 --> 01:05:06,736
-I can't taste anything.
-You can't mess with him now.

1508
01:05:06,802 --> 01:05:08,437
-Don't touch it!
-I can't touch it?

1509
01:05:08,504 --> 01:05:09,572
Just try that.

1510
01:05:09,639 --> 01:05:11,941
-That? Wait. One, two…
-Just eat that.

1511
01:05:12,008 --> 01:05:13,576
I think he made around two bites.

1512
01:05:14,143 --> 01:05:15,544
-I can see it.
-I can tell from here.

1513
01:05:15,611 --> 01:05:17,680
It's about two bites with this spoon.

1514
01:05:17,747 --> 01:05:19,982
You think so, right?
But this is a good portion.

1515
01:05:20,049 --> 01:05:22,585
-Because it'll get bigger?
-Yes.

1516
01:05:24,253 --> 01:05:27,356
HE PUTS THE GRILLED
CUTLASS FISH ON A TRAY

1517
01:05:27,423 --> 01:05:29,492
HE PUTS THEM BACK INTO A DRY PAN

1518
01:05:29,558 --> 01:05:33,262
7. PLACE THE GRILLED CUTLASS FISH
FILLETS ONTO A DRY PAN

1519
01:05:33,329 --> 01:05:35,665
-And here…
-Try the enoki.

1520
01:05:35,731 --> 01:05:36,732
The enoki?

1521
01:05:36,799 --> 01:05:37,833
You're in for a surprise.

1522
01:05:37,900 --> 01:05:40,303
-He used <i>ramyeon </i>soup base.
-Oh, you're right.

1523
01:05:40,369 --> 01:05:43,539
If you fry enoki in high temperature,
it'll taste like crab meat.

1524
01:05:43,606 --> 01:05:45,508
Enoki can taste like crab meat?

1525
01:05:46,075 --> 01:05:47,643
Does it taste like crab?

1526
01:05:47,710 --> 01:05:50,413
-I see. Crab meat?
-Crab meat? Really?

1527
01:05:50,479 --> 01:05:52,515
WILL THE MUSHROOM
TASTE LIKE CRAB MEAT?

1528
01:05:52,581 --> 01:05:53,816
-Really?
-Really?

1529
01:05:53,883 --> 01:05:56,218
-It tastes like crab meat.
-Really?

1530
01:05:56,285 --> 01:06:00,656
It's like the processed crab meat
that we buy and tear off.

1531
01:06:00,723 --> 01:06:02,692
-It tastes like that.
-Really?

1532
01:06:02,758 --> 01:06:04,260
That's so cool.

1533
01:06:04,760 --> 01:06:06,495
HE'S DONE!

1534
01:06:06,562 --> 01:06:08,097
He's finally done.

1535
01:06:08,831 --> 01:06:12,101
-He's done.
-He's getting started.

1536
01:06:12,168 --> 01:06:13,736
-All right.
-He's done.

1537
01:06:13,803 --> 01:06:16,005
He's now cooking the pasta.

1538
01:06:16,072 --> 01:06:18,274
-Will you cook it, then fry it?
-Three minutes.

1539
01:06:18,341 --> 01:06:19,875
I hope the portion is big enough.

1540
01:06:19,942 --> 01:06:21,210
-Do you have to carve that too?
-That again?

1541
01:06:21,277 --> 01:06:23,679
-The zucchini.
-He's making tiny zucchini pieces.

1542
01:06:23,746 --> 01:06:25,514
-My gosh.
-Chef Hyun-suk,

1543
01:06:25,581 --> 01:06:27,783
I have so much respect for you.

1544
01:06:27,850 --> 01:06:28,985
Why is he doing that?

1545
01:06:29,051 --> 01:06:31,654
-"Why is he doing that?
-Why is he digging it up?

1546
01:06:31,721 --> 01:06:33,522
He's making grain shapes again.

1547
01:06:34,223 --> 01:06:36,726
The pasta is getting a bit bigger.

1548
01:06:36,792 --> 01:06:38,260
-Is it?
-It's getting bigger.

1549
01:06:38,327 --> 01:06:41,330
GRILLED CUTLASS FISH,
SOY-BASED SAUCE

1550
01:06:42,398 --> 01:06:44,967
He's starting to braise the fish.

1551
01:06:45,668 --> 01:06:48,137
8. POUR THE SOY-BASED SAUCE
OVER THE GRILLED FISH AND BRAISE

1552
01:06:48,204 --> 01:06:49,638
-The braised cutlass fish.
-The braise.

1553
01:06:49,705 --> 01:06:51,374
-Okay.
-The cutlass fish.

1554
01:06:51,440 --> 01:06:54,844
-Jung-hwan, will you taste the sauce?
-Yes?

1555
01:06:54,910 --> 01:06:56,512
-It looks so good.
-Will it taste fishy?

1556
01:06:56,579 --> 01:06:59,982
-I'll try this.
-He's going to try the sauce.

1557
01:07:00,983 --> 01:07:02,151
How does it taste?

1558
01:07:02,218 --> 01:07:04,854
Does it taste fishy?

1559
01:07:06,088 --> 01:07:07,089
Does it?

1560
01:07:07,156 --> 01:07:09,492
-Does it taste fishy?
-Does it?

1561
01:07:10,693 --> 01:07:12,361
It's not fishy!

1562
01:07:12,428 --> 01:07:15,297
It doesn't taste fishy at all.
It's amazing.

1563
01:07:15,364 --> 01:07:20,202
It tastes like the sauce I had in Nagoya
when I had eel over rice.

1564
01:07:20,269 --> 01:07:22,038
-It's amazing.
-That's Kang-rok.

1565
01:07:22,104 --> 01:07:25,307
BECOME DELICIOUS, CUTLASS FISH,
I PUT IN A LOT OF WORK

1566
01:07:25,374 --> 01:07:27,343
-It's boiling over.
-It's boiling over.

1567
01:07:27,410 --> 01:07:28,544
It's boiling over.

1568
01:07:29,478 --> 01:07:31,347
-The fire went out.
-The fire.

1569
01:07:31,414 --> 01:07:32,748
-It went off.
-Oh, no.

1570
01:07:32,815 --> 01:07:34,383
I'm sorry,
but do you enjoy raw flour dough?

1571
01:07:34,450 --> 01:07:36,552
-No.
-Turn the heat back on.

1572
01:07:36,619 --> 01:07:38,287
Or it's just rice puffs.

1573
01:07:38,354 --> 01:07:39,588
-Rice puffs.
-Rice puffs.

1574
01:07:39,655 --> 01:07:40,756
It'll be just rice puffs.

1575
01:07:40,823 --> 01:07:43,759
-They look like rice puffs.
-Don't they? Rice puffs.

1576
01:07:43,826 --> 01:07:46,929
HE QUICKLY PUTS
OLIVE OIL INTO A PAN

1577
01:07:47,496 --> 01:07:50,533
MASTER GARLIC
DIDN'T FORGET HIS GARLIC

1578
01:07:55,704 --> 01:07:57,540
9. FRY MINCED GARLIC
IN A PAN WITH HEATED OLIVE OIL

1579
01:07:57,606 --> 01:07:58,607
Two minutes!

1580
01:07:58,674 --> 01:08:01,210
KANG-ROK GETS
THE INSTANT RICE READY

1581
01:08:02,511 --> 01:08:03,879
He's making a lunch box.

1582
01:08:03,946 --> 01:08:06,248
It looks good. It looks so good.

1583
01:08:06,315 --> 01:08:08,684
9. PUT RICE INTO A BOX AND POUR
THE SOY-BASED SAUCE OVER RICE

1584
01:08:09,852 --> 01:08:11,387
HYUN-SUK IS IN A RUSH

1585
01:08:12,555 --> 01:08:14,523
-He won't have time.
-A minute and 30 seconds.

1586
01:08:14,590 --> 01:08:15,724
Isn't that Sylvia?

1587
01:08:15,791 --> 01:08:17,860
-Sylvia?
-Hey, Sylvia!

1588
01:08:17,927 --> 01:08:20,329
So Chef Hyun-suk kept Sylvia.

1589
01:08:21,997 --> 01:08:24,667
IT'S TIME TO CHECK
THE GRAIN PASTA!

1590
01:08:25,167 --> 01:08:27,870
-Hey.
-That's a good portion.

1591
01:08:27,937 --> 01:08:30,506
The portion…

1592
01:08:30,573 --> 01:08:32,575
-It got bigger.
-I think it got bigger.

1593
01:08:32,641 --> 01:08:36,245
Da-hee, you had a lot of food
from the round before, right?

1594
01:08:36,312 --> 01:08:38,581
This won't be enough for you.
It's too little.

1595
01:08:38,647 --> 01:08:40,316
Yes, she eats much more than we expected.

1596
01:08:40,382 --> 01:08:42,618
-One minute.
-One minute.

1597
01:08:42,685 --> 01:08:44,487
Will the pasta get cooked?

1598
01:08:44,553 --> 01:08:46,088
He has a minute left,
but his butter isn't even melted.

1599
01:08:46,155 --> 01:08:48,991
-Oh, no.
-Look at the time.

1600
01:08:49,058 --> 01:08:50,960
Chef Kang-rok is almost done.

1601
01:08:51,026 --> 01:08:53,729
-Braised cutlass fish over rice.
-Braised cutlass fish over rice.

1602
01:08:53,796 --> 01:08:56,132
-He has a minute left.
-A minute.

1603
01:08:56,198 --> 01:08:58,467
-Don't let the fish fillet break.
-One minute!

1604
01:08:58,534 --> 01:08:59,902
Oh, my gosh!

1605
01:08:59,969 --> 01:09:01,971
He may end up serving it in Sylvia.

1606
01:09:02,037 --> 01:09:03,539
-How is it?
-Hurry.

1607
01:09:03,606 --> 01:09:05,007
He has 50 seconds.

1608
01:09:05,074 --> 01:09:07,042
They've become bigger, though.

1609
01:09:08,444 --> 01:09:10,880
-It's become much bigger.
-I see.

1610
01:09:10,946 --> 01:09:12,748
-Forty seconds.
-Is it done already?

1611
01:09:13,582 --> 01:09:15,317
-Really? It's done?
-He's plating it.

1612
01:09:15,384 --> 01:09:17,286
-Gosh.
-No way.

1613
01:09:17,353 --> 01:09:18,454
It was cooked that quickly?

1614
01:09:18,521 --> 01:09:20,222
You have 40 seconds.

1615
01:09:20,289 --> 01:09:25,628
-It doesn't look like a big portion.
-No, but the plate is big.

1616
01:09:25,694 --> 01:09:27,196
-Are you done?
-Thirty seconds.

1617
01:09:27,263 --> 01:09:29,431
He's done. Chef Hyun-suk is done.

1618
01:09:29,498 --> 01:09:32,468
-Thirty seconds.
-Oh, my. He had a plan all along.

1619
01:09:32,535 --> 01:09:33,869
Hyun-suk is done.

1620
01:09:33,936 --> 01:09:34,937
Mr. Braise!

1621
01:09:35,004 --> 01:09:36,739
Everything comes down to Mr. Braise.

1622
01:09:36,805 --> 01:09:38,908
-Twenty seconds.
-Twenty seconds, Kang-rok.

1623
01:09:38,974 --> 01:09:41,644
You have some time left.
Did you forget anything?

1624
01:09:41,710 --> 01:09:42,711
-No.
-No toppings?

1625
01:09:42,778 --> 01:09:44,547
-This one.
-Take a good look.

1626
01:09:44,613 --> 01:09:46,048
-Ten, nine,
-Ten, nine,

1627
01:09:46,115 --> 01:09:48,817
-eight, seven, six,
-eight, seven, six,

1628
01:09:48,884 --> 01:09:51,587
-five, four, three…
-five…

1629
01:09:51,654 --> 01:09:52,821
He's done.

1630
01:09:55,791 --> 01:09:57,359
Kang-rok is done.

1631
01:09:57,426 --> 01:10:00,129
He served it in a box.

1632
01:10:00,196 --> 01:10:02,031
-It's all done.
-My gosh.

1633
01:10:02,097 --> 01:10:05,267
Those look like rice grains.

1634
01:10:05,334 --> 01:10:08,003
These dishes were prepared
for Da-hee's order…

1635
01:10:08,070 --> 01:10:12,074
<i>First flavors are always so hard</i>

1636
01:10:12,141 --> 01:10:14,143
Both dishes are done.

1637
01:10:14,210 --> 01:10:17,279
This was quite miraculous.

1638
01:10:17,346 --> 01:10:21,483
Chef Hyun-suk finished first,
and he did whip up risotto.

1639
01:10:21,550 --> 01:10:23,285
-Did everything go according to plan?
-Yes.

1640
01:10:23,352 --> 01:10:26,255
Everything went
exactly as planned and calculated.

1641
01:10:26,322 --> 01:10:28,724
I'm sorry, I can't help noticing
that you keep massaging your hands.

1642
01:10:29,358 --> 01:10:32,661
-You're massaging it nonstop.
-The dough was harder than I expected.

1643
01:10:32,728 --> 01:10:35,531
I have to put in more power
if the dough isn't as runny.

1644
01:10:35,598 --> 01:10:37,066
So my hands are a bit swollen.

1645
01:10:37,132 --> 01:10:38,968
-Oh, no.
-But you know,

1646
01:10:39,034 --> 01:10:41,203
I don't mind if my hands are swollen

1647
01:10:41,270 --> 01:10:43,639
as long as Da-hee enjoys her dish.

1648
01:10:44,406 --> 01:10:45,541
I see.

1649
01:10:46,875 --> 01:10:47,876
All right, then.

1650
01:10:47,943 --> 01:10:51,680
She'll try Da-hee Hard Risotto first.

1651
01:10:52,681 --> 01:10:56,051
ENOKI FRIES FRIED
WITH RAMYEON SOUP BASE

1652
01:10:57,253 --> 01:11:01,690
ON TOP OF HOMEMADE RICE GRAINS
MADE WITH LOVE

1653
01:11:02,958 --> 01:11:06,562
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
DA-HEE HARD RISOTTO

1654
01:11:06,629 --> 01:11:10,032
Try the rice grains first,

1655
01:11:10,099 --> 01:11:13,235
then the enoki fries,
and then the two together.

1656
01:11:13,302 --> 01:11:15,738
Try them separately, then together.

1657
01:11:15,804 --> 01:11:17,873
He made the grains with flour dough.

1658
01:11:17,940 --> 01:11:21,577
They look like rice grains,
and they're in similar sizes.

1659
01:11:22,211 --> 01:11:23,879
There's the first encounter.

1660
01:11:23,946 --> 01:11:25,514
HER FIRST ENCOUNTER
WITH THE RISOTTO

1661
01:11:25,581 --> 01:11:27,650
That was the first encounter.

1662
01:11:27,716 --> 01:11:29,084
I wonder how it'll go.

1663
01:11:29,151 --> 01:11:31,754
-Is it undercooked? Is it cooked?
-No.

1664
01:11:31,820 --> 01:11:34,256
-It's fully cooked.
-Is it?

1665
01:11:34,323 --> 01:11:36,725
The enoki fries tasted like shrimp.

1666
01:11:36,792 --> 01:11:38,394
-Exactly.
-Smell it first.

1667
01:11:38,460 --> 01:11:41,964
It tasted a bit like crabs and shrimp.

1668
01:11:42,464 --> 01:11:43,999
MMM

1669
01:11:44,066 --> 01:11:45,067
Right?

1670
01:11:46,001 --> 01:11:47,002
Yes.

1671
01:11:47,069 --> 01:11:48,070
What?

1672
01:11:48,137 --> 01:11:50,673
That was a half-hearted answer.

1673
01:11:50,739 --> 01:11:54,143
It's not that.
You said it tasted like crabs,

1674
01:11:54,209 --> 01:11:56,779
so I probably expected
to have a strong crab taste.

1675
01:11:56,845 --> 01:11:59,381
At first, it tastes like fried enoki,

1676
01:11:59,448 --> 01:12:02,184
but the more I chew on it,
the more I can taste crab.

1677
01:12:02,251 --> 01:12:04,186
-Right? It tastes like shrimp later.
-Yes.

1678
01:12:04,253 --> 01:12:05,587
-What?
-Shrimp…

1679
01:12:05,654 --> 01:12:07,189
-Shrimp. Yes, you're right.
-I tasted it.

1680
01:12:07,256 --> 01:12:09,892
-I get what you mean.
-You do, right?

1681
01:12:09,958 --> 01:12:14,797
-Why is that? Is it the soup base?
-I don't know.

1682
01:12:15,531 --> 01:12:19,835
She's mixing the two with her spoon
and trying it together.

1683
01:12:19,902 --> 01:12:23,105
-Will it be a successful first encounter?
-Let's see.

1684
01:12:23,172 --> 01:12:24,273
MMM

1685
01:12:24,807 --> 01:12:26,775
It's good.

1686
01:12:26,842 --> 01:12:30,179
-It's good. It's really good.
-Is it?

1687
01:12:30,245 --> 01:12:33,782
I guess it's not something you like
as soon as you meet it.

1688
01:12:33,849 --> 01:12:35,718
To be honest,

1689
01:12:35,784 --> 01:12:37,553
it wasn't amazing when I first ate it.

1690
01:12:37,619 --> 01:12:40,055
At first, it tasted like regular risotto,

1691
01:12:40,122 --> 01:12:42,124
but the more I eat it,
it has a different taste.

1692
01:12:42,191 --> 01:12:44,593
-It's not so bad.
-"Not bad."

1693
01:12:44,660 --> 01:12:46,929
I want to get to know it a little more.

1694
01:12:46,995 --> 01:12:49,031
At first, it was a bit unfamiliar,

1695
01:12:49,098 --> 01:12:51,467
but did you get used to it over time?

1696
01:12:51,533 --> 01:12:52,968
Like you think of it when you go home.

1697
01:12:53,035 --> 01:12:54,903
Will you think of that when you go home?

1698
01:12:55,804 --> 01:12:56,905
I guess not.

1699
01:12:57,740 --> 01:13:00,609
I can already tell by her face
that she won't think of it.

1700
01:13:00,676 --> 01:13:02,344
I guess she won't think of it.

1701
01:13:02,411 --> 01:13:06,615
If this was served with pickles…

1702
01:13:06,682 --> 01:13:08,350
-Or jalapeño.
-Yes.

1703
01:13:08,417 --> 01:13:10,686
-That would've been much better.
-Right.

1704
01:13:10,753 --> 01:13:14,056
It's much better to have a sidekick
when you meet a lady for the first time.

1705
01:13:14,123 --> 01:13:16,892
You just left them alone.

1706
01:13:16,959 --> 01:13:19,128
-They feel a bit awkward.
-Exactly.

1707
01:13:19,194 --> 01:13:20,863
-There's no comic relief.
-No.

1708
01:13:20,929 --> 01:13:23,565
She needed that comical sidekick.

1709
01:13:23,632 --> 01:13:26,602
I thought I was already done,

1710
01:13:26,668 --> 01:13:29,738
but the grains stick around in my mouth
and makes me keep chewing.

1711
01:13:29,805 --> 01:13:31,907
And that texture is pretty fun.

1712
01:13:31,974 --> 01:13:33,842
It's chewy and sticky.

1713
01:13:33,909 --> 01:13:37,112
-I've never had this texture before.
-I see.

1714
01:13:37,179 --> 01:13:38,280
That was great.

1715
01:13:38,847 --> 01:13:42,151
HE CUT OUT
THE CUTLASS FISH FILLETS,

1716
01:13:43,285 --> 01:13:46,989
MIXED IT WITH SOY SAUCE,
AND TOPPED IT OVER RICE

1717
01:13:48,290 --> 01:13:52,027
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S LIGHTLY
BRAISED CUTLASS FISH OVER RICE

1718
01:13:52,094 --> 01:13:55,130
This also would've been better
if he served it with pickled radish.

1719
01:13:55,197 --> 01:13:58,333
Well, there's some chili pepper
to clean out her palate.

1720
01:13:59,334 --> 01:14:01,870
-He made chili pepper.
-There's a sidekick.

1721
01:14:01,937 --> 01:14:02,938
HERE'S THE SIDEKICK

1722
01:14:03,005 --> 01:14:04,907
It came with a sidekick.

1723
01:14:04,973 --> 01:14:08,343
-It came with a sidekick.
-The comic relief.

1724
01:14:08,410 --> 01:14:10,078
-There's the comic relief.
-Yes.

1725
01:14:10,145 --> 01:14:12,347
Do I eat the fish first
or with the chili pepper?

1726
01:14:12,414 --> 01:14:13,415
Try it separately first.

1727
01:14:13,482 --> 01:14:17,419
-Try to take a big bite of the fish.
-A big piece of fish.

1728
01:14:17,486 --> 01:14:21,790
He put a lot of work
into the cutlass fish.

1729
01:14:22,458 --> 01:14:23,759
Braised cutlass fish over rice.

1730
01:14:25,093 --> 01:14:28,697
-The two finally met.
-I hope it's good.

1731
01:14:28,764 --> 01:14:31,033
-What will she do with him?
-It's hard to tell.

1732
01:14:31,099 --> 01:14:33,135
-Who is this guy?
-It's hard to tell.

1733
01:14:33,202 --> 01:14:34,903
-No, she likes it.
-She does?

1734
01:14:35,404 --> 01:14:39,341
-She's trying another bite.
-Another bite.

1735
01:14:40,275 --> 01:14:42,044
It's like the fish fillet
your mom deboned.

1736
01:14:43,178 --> 01:14:45,113
-Mom?
-Yes, although I'm a dad.

1737
01:14:45,180 --> 01:14:47,082
The fish her mom deboned?

1738
01:14:47,149 --> 01:14:50,018
My mom has never made it
this easy to eat for me.

1739
01:14:50,085 --> 01:14:51,186
Thank you so much.

1740
01:14:51,253 --> 01:14:54,223
-Even her mom didn't do that for her.
-Yes, the cutlass fish fillets.

1741
01:14:57,159 --> 01:14:58,794
And try the comic relief.

1742
01:14:58,861 --> 01:15:01,997
-There's the comic relief.
-That plays an important role.

1743
01:15:02,064 --> 01:15:04,399
-That sidekick and play a part.
-Yes.

1744
01:15:05,133 --> 01:15:06,468
MMM.

1745
01:15:06,535 --> 01:15:08,170
Was that the wrong sidekick?

1746
01:15:08,237 --> 01:15:10,672
-It was the right one.
-It was the right choice!

1747
01:15:10,739 --> 01:15:13,976
-She's glad the pepper sidekick is there.
-Good call.

1748
01:15:14,042 --> 01:15:17,112
She continues to eat
after the first encounter.

1749
01:15:17,179 --> 01:15:18,447
I'm guessing it's not fishy.

1750
01:15:18,514 --> 01:15:21,650
-No, not at all.
-He managed to get rid of the smell.

1751
01:15:21,717 --> 01:15:23,285
Is it seasoned well?

1752
01:15:23,352 --> 01:15:25,420
-Yes, it's perfect.
-And it's seasoned well.

1753
01:15:25,487 --> 01:15:29,658
Lastly, break up the fish,

1754
01:15:29,725 --> 01:15:31,426
mix it with the rice, and take big bite.

1755
01:15:31,493 --> 01:15:32,928
-Mis it with the rice?
-Mix it with the rice.

1756
01:15:32,995 --> 01:15:34,162
Yes, try to eat a lot of the fish.

1757
01:15:34,730 --> 01:15:36,965
This time, she mixes it with the rice.

1758
01:15:38,534 --> 01:15:43,205
-It's like the fish your mom deboned.
-Stop saying that.

1759
01:15:43,272 --> 01:15:45,574
He's trying to hypnotize her.

1760
01:15:45,641 --> 01:15:49,177
"That fish was deboned by your mom."

1761
01:15:49,244 --> 01:15:51,146
He may even end up chewing it for her.

1762
01:15:52,014 --> 01:15:54,516
-Is it different when it's mixed?
-It looks good.

1763
01:15:54,583 --> 01:15:57,953
It's seasoned much better
when it's mixed with the rice.

1764
01:15:58,887 --> 01:16:01,523
I see. He must've seasoned it perfectly.

1765
01:16:01,590 --> 01:16:06,728
-Let's try Da-hee Hard Risotto.
-Da-hee Hard Risotto.

1766
01:16:06,795 --> 01:16:08,697
-It's interesting.
-What?

1767
01:16:09,565 --> 01:16:12,401
He knows what I like best.

1768
01:16:12,467 --> 01:16:14,436
It's a wonderfully made pasta.

1769
01:16:14,503 --> 01:16:16,738
The texture is perfect, chewy yet soft,

1770
01:16:16,805 --> 01:16:20,809
the sauce is good,
and the fried mushroom is seasoned well.

1771
01:16:20,876 --> 01:16:22,911
-I really enjoyed it.
-I see.

1772
01:16:22,978 --> 01:16:25,414
-I'm a bit annoyed.
-Why?

1773
01:16:25,480 --> 01:16:28,317
It felt like we were going to hang out
for three hours at our first meeting,

1774
01:16:28,383 --> 01:16:31,820
-but it left after a minute.
-It's a shame.

1775
01:16:31,887 --> 01:16:34,623
-I wanted to hang out for three hours.
-I see.

1776
01:16:34,690 --> 01:16:37,125
I want to eat twice the portion of this
in a huge bowl.

1777
01:16:38,293 --> 01:16:41,263
I want to eat twice the portion of this
in a huge bowl,

1778
01:16:41,330 --> 01:16:42,864
taking huge bites at a time.

1779
01:16:42,931 --> 01:16:46,168
-Twice the portion in a bowl?
-He wants to devour it.

1780
01:16:46,234 --> 01:16:51,073
Next, Kang-rok's dish,
Lightly Braised Cutlass fish Over Rice.

1781
01:16:51,139 --> 01:16:54,876
-It's this sauce.
-Yes, this is it.

1782
01:16:54,943 --> 01:16:56,545
-My gosh.
-It tasted amazing.

1783
01:16:56,612 --> 01:16:57,679
What is this?

1784
01:16:58,947 --> 01:17:00,716
I should've tried just one bite.

1785
01:17:01,283 --> 01:17:02,584
MMM

1786
01:17:03,352 --> 01:17:04,820
How was it, DEX?

1787
01:17:07,322 --> 01:17:09,925
I want to eat a whole crock full of this.

1788
01:17:09,992 --> 01:17:11,727
I want to eat a whole crock full of this.

1789
01:17:12,728 --> 01:17:13,729
A crock?

1790
01:17:13,795 --> 01:17:16,732
-I might even use a ladle as my spoon.
-In a crock.

1791
01:17:16,798 --> 01:17:20,235
Eel over rice is served
with a similar type of sauce, right?

1792
01:17:20,302 --> 01:17:23,872
But I liked it much more
when I had it with cutlass fish.

1793
01:17:23,939 --> 01:17:25,741
-I agree.
-That was my personal take.

1794
01:17:25,807 --> 01:17:29,444
It was as if my mom
deboned the fish for me.

1795
01:17:29,511 --> 01:17:31,947
-This won't be easy.
-No.

1796
01:17:32,014 --> 01:17:33,382
Press one for Choi Kang-rok.

1797
01:17:34,082 --> 01:17:35,350
Press two for Choi Hyun-suk.

1798
01:17:36,084 --> 01:17:38,253
Da-hee is about to make her choice.

1799
01:17:38,320 --> 01:17:41,323
I wonder if she hit it off
with one of the dishes.

1800
01:17:41,390 --> 01:17:43,825
-It's tough to choose.
-It is.

1801
01:17:45,093 --> 01:17:48,196
-I pressed a button.
-She pressed one.

1802
01:17:48,263 --> 01:17:50,132
-Why don't we take a look?
-Sure.

1803
01:17:50,198 --> 01:17:52,167
Choi Hyun-suk versus Choi Kang-rok.

1804
01:17:52,234 --> 01:17:54,269
Let's find out the result!

1805
01:17:54,336 --> 01:17:55,737
Show us.

1806
01:17:55,804 --> 01:17:57,673
They had their first encounter.

1807
01:17:57,739 --> 01:18:01,043
Chef Hyun-suk
is trying to get his sixth win,

1808
01:18:01,109 --> 01:18:03,645
whereas Kang-rok is after this big fish.

1809
01:18:03,712 --> 01:18:08,784
Which first flavor did Da-hee enjoy more?

1810
01:18:08,850 --> 01:18:10,485
Who's the winner of this encounter?

1811
01:18:10,552 --> 01:18:12,054
Who is it?

1812
01:18:12,120 --> 01:18:13,255
The winner is…

1813
01:18:16,291 --> 01:18:18,293
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S LIGHTLY
BRAISED CUTLASS FISH OVER RICE WINS

1814
01:18:18,360 --> 01:18:19,361
My gosh.

1815
01:18:19,428 --> 01:18:22,130
Choi Kang-rok wins!

1816
01:18:22,197 --> 01:18:24,533
Choi Kang-rok wins against Choi Hyun-suk!

1817
01:18:25,100 --> 01:18:29,838
Chef Kang-rok wins against Chef Hyun-suk.

1818
01:18:29,905 --> 01:18:33,909
I saw the way he pulled the dough by hand.

1819
01:18:33,975 --> 01:18:37,212
That definitely made it very hard
to come to a decision.

1820
01:18:37,279 --> 01:18:39,915
But when it came to flavor and preference,

1821
01:18:39,981 --> 01:18:43,118
this was more my type of food.

1822
01:18:43,185 --> 01:18:47,389
-You said you didn't really like fish.
-I don't.

1823
01:18:47,456 --> 01:18:48,790
But it was so soft,

1824
01:18:48,857 --> 01:18:51,393
and it didn't smell fishy either.

1825
01:18:51,460 --> 01:18:54,262
I really enjoyed the soft texture
and the sauce.

1826
01:18:54,329 --> 01:18:57,566
Please put the star on Chef Kang-rok!

1827
01:18:57,632 --> 01:19:01,136
Kang-rok wins against Hyun-suk!
Congratulations.

1828
01:19:01,203 --> 01:19:04,272
Kang-rok takes him down!

1829
01:19:04,339 --> 01:19:05,841
The legendary catfish.

1830
01:19:05,907 --> 01:19:07,676
Not only are you legendary,
but you're also handsome.

1831
01:19:07,743 --> 01:19:09,244
You seem to have a great shape.

1832
01:19:09,311 --> 01:19:12,347
He continues to make me curious.

1833
01:19:13,181 --> 01:19:14,649
HE FAILS TO GET HIM

1834
01:19:14,716 --> 01:19:16,118
DEX is here, so let's have a battle.

1835
01:19:16,184 --> 01:19:17,619
I'm sure one of the eight will win.

1836
01:19:17,686 --> 01:19:18,987
No matter who wins, it'll be huge.

1837
01:19:19,554 --> 01:19:21,156
THE CHEFS ARE CORNERED

1838
01:19:21,223 --> 01:19:23,258
-He's insane.
-You, come on out!

1839
01:19:23,325 --> 01:19:24,626
UDT versus the Marines.

1840
01:19:24,693 --> 01:19:26,862
-We may see a twist.
-The Marines.

1841
01:19:26,928 --> 01:19:27,929
Are you serious?

1842
01:19:27,996 --> 01:19:29,231
WHY IS EVERYONE SURPRISED
BY THE RESULT?

1843
01:19:29,297 --> 01:19:31,533
Sam Kim versus Jung Ho-young.

1844
01:19:31,600 --> 01:19:32,768
It'll be six including the rice.

1845
01:19:32,834 --> 01:19:34,402
I'll have seven including the rice.

1846
01:19:34,469 --> 01:19:36,037
<i>I'm a certified Korean chef.</i>

1847
01:19:36,104 --> 01:19:37,472
<i>I know I have a chance.</i>

1848
01:19:37,539 --> 01:19:39,975
-That looks so good.
-It must be good.

1849
01:19:40,041 --> 01:19:41,343
That's the flavor I wanted.

1850
01:19:41,409 --> 01:19:44,012
<i>I believe an in-flight meal</i>
<i>should come in good nutritional balance.</i>

1851
01:19:44,079 --> 01:19:46,148
<i>I'll make sure you enjoy it very much.</i>

1852
01:19:46,214 --> 01:19:48,016
What? It's not hot at all.

